Commentary.Commentary: We are back! Tom Latham and Will Young are the openers for the Kiwis. Ishant Sharma has the new ball in hand.

Now, New Zealand will have to bat well, the wicket has started to play tricks and one believes it is only going to get tougher. They will need a good start if they are to get close to India's total. Remember, they are batting last so they can't give away a big lead. India on the other hand, will hope to get as big as a lead possible.

The New Zealand bowling was all about the two pacers, Tim Southee and Kyle Jamieson. It was the latter who impressed on Day 1 and the former on Day 2. Southee though was the star with a fifer and it was because of him they have kept India intact. Had they got support from the spinners, they could have well kept India under 300. Williamson will not be pleased with the overall effort but surely will be happy with what they have managed to do on Day 2.

Just the one batter for India made most of the start he got and that was the debutant, Shreyas Iyer. He was the star with a bat and scored a brilliant ton. His partnership along with Ravindra Jadeja, who scored a half ton got India out of trouble after they were in a spot of bother at 145 for 4. They entered Day 2 eyeing 400 now wickets at regular intervals have seen them fall well short. Still, they have a good score on the board.

So the Kiwis have made quick work of the two wickets which were remaining after the break! Also, they have managed to keep India under 350 but we still feel, this is a really good score and India are still ahead in the game.
Is that the end of the innings? Sharma has been given out LBW but he reviews. Looks out.

OUT! LBW! Dead straight! Tossed up, on middle. Ishant Sharma comes forward to block but gets hit on the pads. The finger goes up right away. Sharma reviews it but it is a review taken out of hope. No bat on that and Ball Tracker has three reds. That ends the innings and India are bowled out for 345!
On a length, on off. Blocked out.
SIX! High and handsome! On a length, on off. Yadav thumps it straight back over the bowler for a maximum.
Just wide! Full ball, on off. Yadav looks to flick but gets the leading edge. Kyle Jamieson stretches to his left but cannot get to the ball.
Snorter! Length ball, lands on off and shapes away just enough to go past Yadav's attempted flick.
On a length, outside off. Yadav leaves this one.
Kyle Jamieson to bowl from the other end!
Length ball, on the pads. Umesh Yadav works it to mid-wicket.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, around off. Sharma gets his stride to the ball and blocks it.
Almost a wicket! Tossed up, around leg. Sharma looks to block but gets the inside edge. The ball goes to the right of short leg. The fielder dives but cannot hold onto it.
Tossed up, outside off. Left alone.
Ishant Sharma is the last man in!

OUT! BOWLED! First wicket for a spinner in this Test! Patel tosses this up, on the pads. Ashwin makes room and goes for the drive. But the ball lands in the rough and turns sharply. It goes onto hit the stumps and a handy knock by Ashwin comes to an end.
Tossed up, around off. Ravichandran Ashwin goes for the drive but chops it back on the deck.
Welcome back to the second session on Day 2! The players are out in the middle. Ravichandran Ashwin and Umesh Yadav have taken the crease. Ajaz Patel to start the session.
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

The Kiwis, on the other hand, will want to wrap this up quickly after the break. Someone needs to support Southee as he, for now, is the one doing everything. They need the spinners to pull up the socks soon. The visitors will be pleased if they can keep India under 375. Can they do so? Join us at 12:10 pm Local (6:40 am GMT) for the second session and find out.

India will be slightly disappointed with how things went about in the first session. They lost Ravindra Jadeja early and Wriddhiman Saha also did not last for long. Ravichandran Ashwin and Shreyas Iyer did steady things. The latter got to his ton on debut but fell soon after that. India once again lost wickets in pair as Axar Patel followed the centurion. Ashwin though has batted really well and India will hope he along with the tail can take them close to 400.

A really good first session for the Kiwis and they have just the one man to thank and that is Tim Southee! There were 4 wickets taken and all 4 have fallen to him. The hosts would have thought of something over 400 when the day started but the visitors now have a big chance to keep them under that. An exciting first session and the game is nicely poised.

Just short! Lands outside off on a length and then comes back in sharply. Yadav looks to block but gets the outside edge. The ball goes towards first slip. The fielder goes forward but it lands short. That ends an exciting session and it is Lunch on Day 2!
A single as this is cut to deep cover.
FOUR! Well played! Short of a length, outside off. Ashwin goes back and cuts it between second slip and the gully fielder for a boundary.
Full and on the pads. Yadav whips it past mid-wicket and gets one.
Fuller delivery, on off. Blocked out with ease.
Short of a length, outside off. Yadav looks to cut but misses.
Darted down the leg side. Ashwin misses the flick. The keeper does well to collect it.
Loopy ball, on off. Ashwin blocks it off the front foot.
A single as this is pushed down to long on.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Blocked out towards the bowler.
Darted on the pads. Played past square leg for one.
Tossed up, on off. Yadav drives it down the ground. Patel goes down to his left but cannot stop the ball. Single.

Off the mark is Yadav! Full ball, on the pads. He looks to flick it away but gets the leading edge. The man at gully dives to his right but only gets a hand to it. Single and Yadav will keep the strike.
Length ball, lands outside off and shapes away. Yadav leaves this one.
On a length, outside off. Left alone with ease.
Stays low again! Back of a length, around off. Yadav looks to block it from the crease but the ball stays low and goes under his bat.
Full and the on the pads. Flicked to deep mid-wicket for one.
Length ball, around off. Ashwin is beaten as he looks to block.
Change. Finally, Tim Southee gets a break. Kyle Jamieson (20.2-6-77-3) is back now.
Nicely tossed up again, on off. Yadav taps it back to Ajaz Patel.
Fuller and on off. Yadav drills it straight towards mid off.
Flatter and quicker, around off. Yadav blocks it again.
Loopy ball, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Tossed up, on off. Yadav gets forward and blocks it.
Darted on the pads. Ashwin works it past square leg for one.
Yadav survives! Length ball, around off. He blocks it from the crease.
On a length, on off. Yadav stays in the crease and blocks it.
Short ball, outside off. Ashwin goes for the pull but gets the toe end past square leg for one.
On a length, on off. Pushed to long off but they don't take the single.
Short of a length, on the body. It stays a bit low as Ashwin looks to pull. The ball hits his body and rolls to the left of the keeper. Tom Blundell dives and stops it.
Short of a length, outside off. It shapes away after landing so Ashwin leaves it.

FOUR BYES! That turned and kept low! Ashwin won't mind seeing that from the non-striker's end but the Kiwi players won't be liking it. This lands on off and spins away. Stays low too. Yadav is beaten as he tries to block. It goes between the legs of the keeper and down to the third man fence.
Angled into the pads, slightly shorter. Aswhin has time to go back and work it through mid-wicket for one.
Floats it up on off, Ashwin plays it to covers again.
The arm ball, comes back in. Defended.
Tosses it up again and on off, Ashwin again plays it to covers.
On off, this is stroked to covers.
BEATEN! Yadav survives! Length and on off, shapes away again. Yadav plays inside the line and the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Fuller and just outside off, shaping away. Left alone.
Outside off, shaping away. Left alone.
Shorter in length and on middle, this is pulled through square leg for one.
Does not take the run! Probably the right call, he would not want Yadav to face Southee. Outside off, it is guided through point for one.
Swinging away, outside off. Left alone.
A single and Ashwin keeps strike! On middle, he nudges it through square leg.
Steps out but the length is shortened. Blocked.
On off, defended.
Floats it up on off, Ashwin pushes it to covers.
On the stumps again, kept out.
Gives it air and lands it on middle, Ashwin defends.
On off, defended.
Another one which is fuller and moves away. Left alone.
That is a beauty! Length and on off, moves away. Yadav is beaten as he tries to defend.
Angled into the pads, it is worked through square leg for one.
FOUR! Up and over! You would expect more of such shots from Ashwin now! He clears his front leg. This is on a length and on off, it is lofted over covers for a boundary.
Fuller and on middle, Ashwin looks to drive but it goes off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Bowls it quicker but very full and on middle, it is jammed out.
Floats it up on off, blocked again.
On middle, blocked.
Angled into the pads, Ashwin works it through square leg and gets to the other end.
On middle, defended.
Slows it up and on the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Umesh Yadav walks out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Southee is on fire! What a spell. He has bowled right from the start of the day and has delivered big time. His 4th of the day and 5th wicket in total. Another peach of a delivery. Length, gets it to tail back in initially. Patel plays the original trajectory. Southee gets it to straighten after landing. The ball moves enough to take the outside edge and the keeper, Tom Blundell, makes no mistake. It has been New Zealand's morning so far.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Now the inswinger again, on off, Patel guides it to point.
Lovely nut! This time angles it into the off pole, gets it to leave the batter after it lands. Patel is beaten as he tries to block.
Now goes around the wicket, bowls it full and gets it to tail back in. This is pushed to mid off.
This time it is a little too straight, Patel clips it through square leg. Two taken.
From over the wicket, gets it to shape back in from outside off. Defended.
Angled into the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
On middle, defended.
Floats it up outside off, Ashwin pushes it to covers.
Slighty shorter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
On middle, defended.
On off, this is played towards point for one.
FOUR! That is delightful! Fuller and shaping away. Ashwin leans into it and strokes it through covers. He is on 20 in no time.
Makes the batter play this time as it is bowled on off, defended.
Really good swing again. Outside off, shapes away further. Left alone.
Leg bye! Yet another big booming inswinger but on the pads. Patel looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye taken.

Huge, huge appeal but turned down! Southee really liked it but he was the only one appealing. This starts on off and then tails back in a long way. Patel misses the flick. The keeper dives to his right and takes it.
Axar Patel is the next batter.

OUT! TAKEN! The break has worked for the Kiwis and they have gotten the centurion, Iyer. Could have easily had both, Ashwin and Iyer in the last two balls but they will be pretty pleased with this wicket and also how things have gone so far this morning. They are now into the bowlers. A loose stroke by Iyer. Probably lapse in concentration there. Southee's ploy though of bowling it outside off works again. It is another driving-length delivery. Probably a little behind that length. Holds in the surface a touch. Iyer is early in the drive, it goes straight into the hands of the cover fielder and Will Young takes it. Southee has his 4th and third of Day 2.
Commentary.Howout: c Will Young b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks! A very exciting session so far. Southee has bowled brilliantly but Jamieson was quite wayward. The key for India remains this stand as there is not much batting to follow.  They would want Iyer to score a big ton and carry his bat.

Stumping chance goes abegging! Ajaz Patel would have loved a wicket here. Lovely delivery. Gives it good flight. Ashwin's eyes lit up as he steps down. The ball dips at the end, Ashwin swings, this one lands and also stays low. Goes under the bat. The keeper does not get his gloves down in time. This could prove costly.
Loopy ball on off, Ashwin pushes it to covers.
Floats it up on off, blocked.
Skips down the track now and hits it hard to the man at mid off. One taken.
Better! Slows it up and lands it on middle, this one turns away after landing. Iyer looks to defend but it goes off the outer half on the off side.
Does not start off that well! Drifts one down the leg side, this is worked down to fine leg for three. Patel needs to be good, he was not at his best on Day 1.
Ajaz Patel (21-6-78-0) is on now!
Continues to keep it wide outside off, Ashwin drives, he gets it through covers, this time there is a sweeper so only one.

FOUR! Through the off side yet again! On the fuller side, shapes away again. Ashwin looks to drive, he does go hard at it, the ball goes more off a thickish outside edge through cover-point. Boundary. Two in a row. 300 up.
FOUR! Really nicely played! Fuller and outside off, shapes away. Ashwin leans forward, he opens the face of the bat at the very end, adjusts to the swing and plays it through point. Boundary.
Good length again and on off, Ashwin defends it right under his eyes.
Another one wide outside off, Ashwin shoulders arms to this one.
Angled into the middle pole, Ashwin defends it back to the bowler.
Length ball, on the sixth-stump line. Iyer covers his stumps and then leaves it.
Length ball, on the pads. Worked to mid-wicket.
Full and wide outside off. It shapes away but Iyer won't chase that. Kyle Jamieson has been quite wayward with his lines this morning.
Short of a length, around off. Iyer goes back to block it.
Short of a length, around off. Ashwin pushes it past covers and takes a single.
Fuller ball, on off. Ashwin works it to mid on.
Short of a length, shapes away a bit after landing on the fourth stump. Iyer shoulders his arms to it.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.

Similar delivery and Ashwin gets the outside edge towards cover. He wants one but is sent back. The fielder fires a direct hit at the keeper's end and the ball rolls away. Ashwin takes a single now. Southee is not happy with Ashwin. The batter had taken a few steps forward right through the center of the pitch and turned back. The umpire has a word with Ashwin now.
Outswinger but this starts on middle. Ashwin looks to block but gets the outside edge past point for a couple. He is off the mark.
Ravichandran Ashwin walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Good catch behind the sticks but this has been a brilliant spell by Southee! He kept bowling on the stumps to Saha and this time, he serves a full one, outside off. Saha's eyes lit up and he goes for the drive. But the ball nips away just enough to get the outside edge. Tom Blundell dives to his right and takes it. Southee has been on fire for the Kiwis in this session.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Full now, on off. But Saha is equal to the task and blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Edged again! Fuller ball, lands outside off and shapes away. Iyer goes for the drive but gets the outside edge. The ball runs past backward point and races to the fence.
Back of a length, outside off. Left alone.
Length ball, way outside off and Iyer won't chase it.
Full but drifting on the pads. Iyer looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
Full ball, on off. Blocked out.

A TON ON DEBUT! This is what he must have dreamt of as a kid and Shreyas Iyer has achieved this dream. He becomes the 16th Indian player to get a debut ton in Tests. Fuller ball, outside off. He guides it through point to get to the milestone! Length and around off, Iyer opens the face and plays it past gully.
Full again, on off. Blocked out.
Full ball, on off. Blocked out.
Short of a length, on the pads. Worked past square leg for one.
Another wide one as Southee wants Iyer to drive it. But the Mumbai lad leaves this one.
Fuller and closer to the off pole. Pushed to covers.
Length ball, starts wide outside off and swings in the air and nips away after landing. Iyer comes forward but then leaves it alone.
Short of a length, wide outside off. Dragged to deep mid-wicket for one. Iyer moves to 97 and will keep the strike.
Short ball, outside off. Iyer rises and then drags it to the leg side. The man at short mid-wicket dives to his right and stops it.
Full ball, on off. Pushed to mid off.
FOUR! Oh, this is glorious! Length ball, around off. Iyer shifts his weight forward, gets to the pitch and then drives it nicely to the cover fence.

FOUR! Edged but a boundary! Iyer into the 90s now. Length ball, just outside off. Iyer looks to block from the crease. He plays with soft hands so the outside edge falls well short of the slip cordon. It goes past the fielder and runs to the third man fence.
Length ball, on off. Iyer blocks it from the crease.
Length ball, on off. Saha comes forward to block this one.
Shorter ball, way outside off. Saha is not going to chase that one.
A bit of shape for Tim Southee on this occasion but the ball is outside off. So, Saha lets Tom Blundell collect it again.
Length ball, on the fifth stump. Saha shoulders his arms to this one.
A touch fuller, on off. Saha gets to the pitch of the ball and taps it with soft hands towards cover.
Good-length ball, outside off. Saha gets forward and then leaves it alone.
FOUR! No stopping that one and Iyer moves closer to his ton! Short of a length, quite a bit of width too. Iyer plays it past point and the ball races to the fence.
Short of a length, just outside off. Shreyas punches it well but the man at covers gets to his left and gathers the ball.
Full ball, down the leg side. Worked to deep square leg for one. Saha is off the mark.
Fuller ball, outside off. Saha is solid in his defence.
Short of a length, just outside off. Iyer pushes it past covers for one.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Wriddhiman Saha walks out to bat now!

OUT! BOWLED! Chopped on! Southee delivers for his skipper. On a length, just outside off. Jadeja has his feet glued to the crease as he looks to block it. The ball comes back in with the angle, takes the inside edge and then crashes onto the stumps! A brilliant start for the Kiwis and they would want to take a couple of more wickets. Actually, just before this ball was bowled, the fielder at square leg was pushed back towards the fence. That could have had Jadeja anticipating a shorter ball. His feet were glued to the crease here and that field positioning could well be the reason! Good tactics by the Kiwis!
Length ball, on off. Jadeja stays in the crease and blocks it out.
Slipped fuller and on the stumps. Jadeja works it to mid on.
A bit wider outside of this time. Jadeja prods forward and then lets the keeper collect it.
Southee draws Jadeja forward. The southpaw does come forward to this length ball and blocks it towards cover.
Short of a length, outside off. Jadeja stays in the crease and punches it really well. But the man at short cover dives to his right and stops the ball.
A solid front-foot defence by Iyer to end the over. 8 from it.
FOUR! Nicely done by Iyer! Short of a length, wide enough for Iyer to open the face of the bat and play it past point for a boundary.
Short of a length, outside off. Iyer goes back and then blocks it with ease.
Length ball, just outside off. Iyer leans into it and blocks it towards cover.
Length ball, around off. Iyer blocks it out.
Who will bowl from the other end? Kyle Jamieson it is. He was brilliant yesterday. Can he get an early wicket for his side?
FOUR! Lovely shot! Kyle Jamieson goes full but on the pads. Iyer whips it away and bags a boundary.
Length ball, on off. Pushed to covers.
Review time! A huge appeal for an LBW is turned down. New Zealand review. Looks a tad high. Probably umpire's call.

NOT OUT! Umpire's call on wickets hitting! Southee gets this one to jag back in sharply. It lands on a length, outside off and comes in sharply with the angle. Jadeja is stuck to the crease while looking to block and gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but the umpire is unmoved. It looks like a good appeal and Kane Williamson decides to review it. There is no bat on it but Ball Tracker has it as umpire's call on hitting as the ball is clipping the top of the stumps. Jadeja would have had his heart in the mouth for a moment!
This lands outside off and comes in a long way with the angle. But, it is still wide enough for Jadeja to leave it.
Good-length ball, around the fifth-stump line. Ravindra Jadeja leaves it again.
Fuller and closer to the off pole. Jadeja prods forward and then leaves it alone.
Southee starts with a length ball, quite wide outside off. Jadeja watches this one sail into the gloves of Tom Blundell.
Time for the action to begin now! The two batters, Shreyas Iyer and Ravindra Jadeja walk out to resume their innings. Tim Southee to begin proceedings for the visitors. Here we go...

Pitch Report - Deep Dasgupta is down for the pitch report. He says that the first day belonged to the batters. Dominic Cork joins him and says that there was not too much bounce on Day 1 and there could be more variable bounce as the game goes on. Adds that the cracks near the good-length area are starting to open and that could assist the spinners. Deep Dasgupta says that the pitch is quite slow and might give the batters that extra bit of time to adjust to the spin.

Yes, the New Zealand spinners weren't that great but how good were Iyer and Jadeja? Especially the former! What a knock from him on debut and he is still not done! He did not try to change his game, played with attacking intent and has really shone. A ton on debut is on the offer here and he will be hungry to get to that milestone. Jadeja, on the other hand, keeps getting better and better with the bat with each passing game. He has made it a habit to bail the hosts out of trouble then and again. Both will love to get to the three-figure mark and if they continue to play the way they did at the end of Day 1, we will not have to wait long to see that happen. Day 2 is considered the best day to bat so they would want to cash in.

New Zealand's ploy of going with just the two pacers really did not work! It was the seamers who reaped rewards and the spinners really struggled. Had one of Ajaz Patel or William Somerville had a good day, the visitors could have well been in a better position here. They have let the advantage slip away and the hosts could end up putting a pretty big total in the first innings.

A counter-attacking partnership between Iyer and Jadeja took India on top after they were in a slight bother at 145 for 4. With 6 wickets in hand, India are well on course to get to a really good first innings score. However, the Kiwis would know they are just a couple of wickets away from entering the lower-order. The second new ball is just the 4 overs old and the Kiwis need to make use of it. Can they surge a fightback or will it be yet another long day in the field for them? Welcome to the coverage of Day 2 of the first Test between India and New Zealand.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

Right then. That has been a fantastic day of cricket for India on Day 1 and they will be looking to continue the good work come Day 2, whereas, the Kiwis will be hoping to use the new cherry to break this stand between Iyer and Jadeja and then, will want to make further inroads. The action on Day 2 will begin at 9.30 am local (4 am GMT). We hope to have your company. See ya!

Kyle Jamieson has a quick chat! He says that it was nice to bowl on this deck and it was good to have some swing and they hung in there for large parts but is happy with their effort. Says that he has not played in the last couple of months and it is good to play Test cricket and get into his rhythm. Hopes that the new ball swings in the morning and they have their work cut out for them. Opines that India is a fraction ahead but they have done well and a lot depends on how they perform tomorrow morning too.

A great day for India overall! India were off to a sedate start but lost Mayank Agarwal early. Shubman Gill and Cheteshwar Pujara steadied the ship for India for a while as both kept the scoreboard ticking where the former also got to his fourth Test fifty and were remained unscathed till Lunch. However, post Lunch, Gill was sent back and Pujara followed him soon. Both the set batters were sent packing and then it was up to Rahane and Iyer to take India to safer shores. Rahane did look good for the most part but could not build on his start and India were four down before Tea. The onus was then on Iyer and Jadeja to take India to safer shores and they did exactly that as both the batters marched along quickly and didn't allow the situation to get them in mind. Both the batters batted exceedingly well throughout and scored more than 100 runs in the last session. Shreyas Iyer was the most impressive as he brought his maiden Test fifty while Ravindra Jadeja too got to his fifty later. The duo joined the force and are unbeaten with a 113-run stand and will look to continue to boss the Kiwis on Day 2 as well.

The New Zealand bowlers were simply exceptional in these Asian conditions. The cracks opened up soon enough but it was their pacers who managed to trouble the Indian batters, particularly Kyle Jamieson. He kept hitting probing lines and lengths and was finally rewarded with the wicket of Mayank Agarwal. That was the only wicket they got in the first session but post-Lunch, Kyle Jamieson struck straightaway for the Kiwis as he removed the set Shubman Gill and later picked the prized wicket of Ajinkya Rahane, while Southee got the better off Pujara. New Zealand were in a commanding position but post the second session couldn't manage to keep India completely on the back foot as they found it tough to get wickets. Ajaz Patel kept spraying the ball down the leg side, into the rough to get some turn but the Indian batters weren't troubled by that even a tiny bit. They took the new ball immediately and bowled a couple of overs but bad light meant that the umpires had to call it a day.

The two teams had their say in the first session, but it was India who were slightly on top at the stroke of Lunch, then New Zealand dominated the second session and undoubtedly, the third session belonged to India. They will be very happy with what they have got on the board and the dressing room gives applause as well to Shreyas Iyer and Ravindra Jadeja who are unbeaten with a 113-run stand.
The umpires have decided that the light is not good enough to continue and hence, this will be STUMPS ON DAY 1!
Loopy ball, on middle, nudged on the leg side.
Full again, around off. Iyer blocks it out.
Full and on off, Iyer stays solid in defence.
On middle, blocked out.
SIX! Iyer is batting like he has been playing this format for years. William Somerville tosses it up, on middle. Shreyas Iyer comes forward and smokes it over deep square leg for a biggie.
Loopy ball, on middle. Iyer punches it towards the left of the bowler.
Full and outside off, pushed to covers.
Down leg, Iyer misses his glance. The keeper fails to collect the ball cleanly and the batters take a bye.

JAFFA! Back of a length, outside off, nipping away. Shreyas Iyer has a poke at it but misses. He was sucked into the drive but Southee got this to leave the batter very late. That was very close to the outside edge and the off pole.

The lightmeter is out from the umpire. They are checking the light right now as we near the end of play on Day 1. Looks like the umpires have asked Kane Williamson to get his spinners in and remove the seamers as they have adjudged that the light is not good enough for pace bowling. So, William Somerville is back into the attack now!

FIFTY FOR JADEJA! Back of a length, on off. Ravindra Jadeja hops and punches it to mid off. He scampers across for a quick single. The fielder throws the ball to the keeper who whips the bails off but Shreyas Iyer made it in time. Jadeja gets to his fifty and brings out his sword celebration. His 17th Test fifty and a big round of applause from the dressing room. He has been very consistent for India in this format for a while now.
On a good length, in the corridor of uncertainty. Jadeja dabs it to gully.
Length ball, well outside off for Jadeja to offer a shot.
Length ball, outside off. Jadeja reaches out for it and drives it through covers. The fielder dives to his right but fails to stop. He pushes hard for the second run but settles for a single.
Outside off, coming back in. Jadeja leaves it untouched.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Jadeja tucks it to mid on.
FOUR! Make that two in a row! The new ball is coming on nicely to the bat. Short of a length, outside off. Ravindra Jadeja hops and punches it through covers for another boundary. Moves onto 48 now!

FOUR! Poor from Kyle Jamieson! Length ball, down the leg side. Ravindra Jadeja helps it on its way to fine leg for a boundary. That also brings up the 100-run partnership between Shreyas Iyer and Ravindra Jadeja.
On a nagging length, outside off. Ravindra Jadeja comes forward and has a poke but gets beaten all ends up.
Short of a length, on off. Iyer covers the line and defends it on the leg side. A maiden from Tim Southee with the new cherry.
Change in bowling. As expected, Kyle Jamieson returns into the action. 14.2-6-38-3 are his numbers so far!
Length ball, outside off. Iyer leaves it alone.

...DAY 1, SESSION 3...

New Zealand will be beaming looking at how this session has gone by. Since this is a comparatively inexperienced Indian side, they have removed the spine of this Indian batting, which would be Gill, Pujara, and Rahane. It has been the Kyle Jamieson show for them since the first session as the tall lad has made the ball swing both ways and also took the wickets of both Gill and Rahane in this session. Southee too removed Pujara but was in some discomfort and his injury might be a concern. Their spinners have been good too, but have not taken any wickets so far. Can India's batters continue and swell their score up? Or will the Kiwis run through India's batters and make life difficult in the last session? Join us at 2.30 pm local (9 am GMT) for the third and final session.

If the first session belonged largely to India, then, this one certainly would be under the name of New Zealand. They have done extremely well to cut through India's batting lineup, getting rid of three Indian batters and not letting the hosts score runs easily. Right after the Lunch break, India lost Gill, who was looking good out in the middle. Not long after this, Pujara too made his way back to the shed as Southee hunted him down. Rahane and Iyer looked set to take India to safer shores, until the Tea break at least, but Rahane did not redeem himself as his average form continued and he could not build on his start. Since then, Iyer and Jadeja steered India safely and would want to continue the good work in the final session.

Outside off again, short again, left alone again.
WIDE. This time, he overdoes it. Another bouncer, outside off, bounces way over Pujara's head, to the keeper. Wide signalled.
Another bouncer this time, does not bounce too much, as Pujara was looking to duck. He just about gets his shoulder underneath the ball as the cherry goes to the keeper behind.
A bumper this time for Pujara, who easily sits under this one.
Cheteshwar Pujara is getting some treatment on his fingers. We are ready to resume now. Kyle Jamieson to continue.
Full, on off, Ajinkya Rahane goes back and blocks it out to the off side.
Ajinkya Rahane presses forward this time and solidly defends it.
A carbon copy of the previous delivery. Again, Rahane finds the fielder.
Floated around off, eased to the cover fielder.
Fuller around off, defended out.
On middle, kept out.
Short on off, awkwardly fended out by Pujara.

FOUR! Short and wide and Cheteshwar Pujara will not leave that unpunished. First boundary on the 75th delivery for Pujara. Wider outside off, Cheteshwar Pujara hops slightly and slaps this through cover-point for a boundary.
Served on a shorter trajectory, closer to the off pole, Rahane bends his back and sways away. Another no ball as Kyle Jamieson continues to overstep his boundary.
Around off, pushed to covers, where the fielder misfields and they can take a run.
Outside off, left alone.

FOUR! That's the first boundary for the Indian skipper. That will give him some confidence. Short of a length, outside off, does not rise too much, Ajinkya Rahane goes back and punches this through covers. Ajaz Patel chases after this but the ball wins the race to the ropes.
NO BALL! Around off, pushed to covers. Kyle Jamieson oversteps yet again.

Rahane lost track of where the ball was for a second or two there. He has a wry smile on his face and so does Kyle Jamieson. Short this time, outside off, Rahane looks to pull but only manages to underedge this one to the keeper on the bounce. Ajinkya Rahane looks around and realizes that the ball is behind him.
Lunges forward this time and blocks it out nicely, does Pujara.
An action replay of the previous delivery.
On middle, flicked to square leg.

'RUN, RUN, RUN, RUN, RUN!' says Pujara and they complete two here. A full toss, around off, Cheteshwar Pujara gets ahead and pushes this to the left of mid on. Cheteshwar Pujara wants one and scampers through. The fielder though misfields and they are allowed to get another.
Goes fuller again, but this time on off and middle, Pujara gets forward and keeps it out solidly.
Fuller on middle and leg, gently dabbed down onto the deck.
Outside off, Ajinkya Rahane works this to covers. A maiden now for Kyle!
Down the leg side, the flick is missed.
On a length, wider outside off, lands and nips in, Rahane shoulders arms on this occasion.
On off, blocked out by Ajinkya.
Slightly fuller, on off, defended out.
A short delivery to begin for Rahane, served outside the off pole. He does not make a hassle out of this and leaves it easily.
On middle, kept out.
Outside off, shorter now, the cut shot is employed but straight to the point fielder.
Short now, around off, lands and turns away as Pujara waits, and then taps this to covers.
Cheteshwar Pujara steps out, but his whip only finds the mid-wicket fielder.
Slightly outside off, fuller again, gently pushed away to the off side.
Floated, around off, kept out.
The Indian skipper, Ajinkya Rahane walks out to bat. Also, Ajaz Patel to bowl from the other end.

OUT! BOWLED 'EM! Kyle Jamieson continues to trouble the Indian batters. Gill was looking very solid out there and looked to be running away to a big score has been sent packing for 52, right in the first over after the Lunch break. Kyle Jamieson has been right on the money throughout the game so far and he follows the same template here. He serves it on a length, in the fourth stump channel, with a hint of inward movement. Shubman Gill looks to push this to the off side but the inward movement ensures that the ball kisses the inside edge and crashes into the furniture behind. Gill trudges back this time and the Kiwis have struck at the right time!
Short of a length, on off, Gill hops and nudges this to the mid-wicket fielder.
Around off, on a length, Gill pushes this to covers.
In the corridor of uncertainty outside off, left alone by Gill.
A hint of inswing! Around off, back of a length, the ball nips in this time, SG fends this one off to the leg side.
Kyle Jamieson starts this new session with a shortish delivery, around off too, Shubman Gill lines up to play the pull shot but gets an inside edge back onto his pad.
We are ready for the second session! New Zealand players stride out to the middle. Cheteshwar Pujara and Shubman Gill jog out to the middle as well. Kyle Jamieson to start things off.
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

India were off to a good start as Mayank Agarwal and Shubman Gill batted well at the start and the former tried to keep the scoreboard ticking while the latter took his time to settle. Shubman Gill was adjudged lbw in the third over but the review saved him as he was very confident of getting an inside edge which proved to be right. However, Mayank Agarwal departed soon getting an outside edge to Jamieson. After that, Shubman Gill took on Ajaz Patel to get some runs under the belt while Cheteshwar Pujara battled out the spinners well and the duo brought up the 50-run partnership and steadied the ship for India. Shubman Gill stood up in the absence of Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul and brought up his half century. He will be looking to continue on his merry way while New Zealand bowlers will be now desperate to get a few scalps. Will they be able to do so? Do join us at 12.10 pm local (6.40 am GMT) for the second session to find out.

New Zealand were right on the money from the word go, particularly Kyle Jamieson, who kept probing with his line and lengths and kept the Indian openers at their toes. The outside edge was just missed a couple of times but Jamieson finally found success scalping Mayank Agarwal. New Zealand could have had Shubman Gill too in the 7th over but they did not opt for a review. That might prove them costly. Ajaz Patel leaked runs while William Somerville and Rachin Ravindra kept things tight from the other end.
India would have wanted a strong start and they have got exactly that despite losing Mayank Agarwal early. They will definitely be the happier side heading into the break.
Very full from William Somerville and around off, Cheteshwar Pujara digs this out to mid off. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!
Tossed up, on off, kept out.
Straying on the pads this time, on a flatter length, Gill nudges this through backward square leg and they take one. Gill denies the second though.
On middle, Shubman Gill again blocks it well.
William Somerville drags his length back and serves it short, outside off, Gill camps back and taps this to the off side.
A touch fuller, around off, Shubman dances down and works it back to the bowler.
Short, on off, pushed to mid off.
Rachin Ravindra continues to bowl fuller to Pujara, who whips this to the right of mid on.
Cheteshwar Pujara's punch this time is straight down the throat of the mid off fielder. No run again.
Very full again on off, CP jams this out past covers, but straight to the mid off fielder.
Rachin Ravindra drags this short now, serves it around off, Gill goes back and punches this to the cover region. They sneak through and complete the run.
Shubman Gill steps forward and blocks it out.
CP clips this one straight to the mid-wicket fielder.
Full, very full on off, CP digs this one out towards mid on. Wants a run but is sent back this time.
Cheteshwar Pujara has just watchfully blocked this out.

Fifty for Shubman Gill! He is back in the team and he starts off nicely. His fourth fifty in Tests and second one in India. A mature knock from the youngster so far and he would look to build on this. Flighted, around off, clipped through mid-wicket for one.
Floated, fuller, around off, SG works this to the right of mid on this time.
Tossed up, on off, knocked to mid on.
A single this time as Shubman knocks this down to long on.
Darted on middle, knocked to the leg side.
Around off, blocked.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.

Spicy turn there! Takes everyone by surprise. Floated, lands fuller around off, the ball hits the deck and spins away massively as Gill defends inside the line and misses. Tom Blundell does well behind the sticks to stop this.
Rachin Ravindra starts with a fuller ball, around off, nicely defended out by Gill.
The debutant, Rachin Ravindra is introduced into the attack.
Cheteshwar Pujara flicks this full ball straight to Southee at mid-wicket.
Cheteshwar Pujara prods forward and keeps this out solidly.
Around off, defended out.
On middle, gently eased down towards long on for a single.
Floated, around off, Pujara skips down and flicks this to mid-wicket. Tim Southee there dives to his left and half-stops the ball, which allows the batsmen to cross ends.
Flatter and around off, pushed back to the bowler.
Ajaz Patel looks to fire down the leg side as Cheteshwar Pujara was continously advancing. Pujara though stays back this time and smartly tickles the full ball to fine leg and collects three runs.
On off, Pujara advances down the track and defends.
Tosses it up, on middle. Pujara looks to defend but gets an inside edge. The ball rolls towards fine leg for a couple of runs.
Loopy ball, around off. Pujara looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads. Ajaz Patel appeals for an lbw but the umpire is not interested.
Outside off, left alone.
Flatter and full, on middle. Pujara knocks it on the leg side.
Loopy ball, on middle, Gill plays it to mid on.
Flighted ball, on leg. Gill defends it out.
Full again, on middle. Pujara uses his feet to flick it behind square on the leg side for one. Brings up the fifty partnership as well between the two batters.
On off, blocked out by Pujara.
Loopy ball, on off. Pujara steps out and wrists it to mid-wicket.
Full and on off, Gill uses his feet and nudges it to long on for a run.
This is flicked to deep square leg for a run.
On the pads, blocked out.
Shortish ball, outside off. Gill goes back and cuts it to backward point.
Very full, on middle. Gill digs it out.
Some turn and low bounce! On off, Shubman Gill looks to defend but the ball beats the outside edge.

FOUR! Just over Kane Williamson at mid off! Floats it up, on leg. Shubman Gill shimmies down and lifts it towards mid off. Kane Williamson takes a leap but the ball goes just over him and into the fence.
On off, Pujara steps out and defends it on the off side.
Fullish delivery, on middle. Gill drives it to long on for a single.
On the pads, worked to mid-wicket.

Half-hearted appeal from the Kiwi players but the umpire is not interested. Loopy ball, on middle, turning back in. Shubman Gill puts a stride forward and looks to defend but misses. The ball goes off the pads and the short leg fielder catches it.
Full and on middle, watchfully blocked out.
Quicker delivery, on middle. Gill steps out and looks to flick but gets an outside edge to mid off.
Flighted delivery, on middle. Pujara blocks this one out off the front foot.
Sprays this one down leg, Pujara looks to tuck it away but misses.
On the pads, worked through mid-wicket for a single.

FOUR! Beautiful timing on that one! Floats it up, on middle and leg. Shubman Gill goes back in the crease and punches it past mid-wicket. The timing was excellent and the ball races away to the boundary.
Full, on middle. Gill is solid in his defence.
Flatter ball, on middle. Gill defends it back to the bowler.
Loopy ball, around off. Pujara guides it to point.
Short and on leg, Pujara knocks it down to mid on.
Full and on the pads, Pujara uses his feet again and flicks it to square leg.
Tosses it up, on middle. Pujara defends it watchfully.
Full and on middle, Pujara prods and defends it on the leg side.
Flighted delivery, on leg. Pujara uses his feet and flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Back of a length, on middle. Gill sits back and knocks it down to mid on.
On a good length, on leg. Gill flicks towards mid-wicket. The fielder dives to his right and stops the ball.
Change. Some more spin for us to witness as the 37-year old, William Somerville is handed the ball.
Length ball, on middle. Gill covers the line nicely and blocks it out.
Short of a length, outside off. Gill punches it to deep cover for a brace.
On a length, on middle. Pujara tucks it to mid-wicket and takes off for a quick single. The fielder has a shy at the bowler's end but misses.
Fullish and on off. Pujara looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
On the pads, Gill blocks it watchfully.
FOUR! Nicely played! Tosses it up, outside off. Shubman Gill makes room for himself and cuts it very late. The ball races away to deep backward point in a flash. 50 comes up for India as well.
Outside off, pushed to covers.
Flatter delivery, on off. Gill defends it out.

SIX! Beautiful shot! Loopy ball, on middle. Shubman Gill advances down the track and smashes it with a straight bat over long on for a biggie. Ajinkya Rahane likes it and applauds the shot from the dugout.
Full and on middle, Gill steps out and defends.
Length ball, on leg. Gill tucks it behind square on the leg side for one.
On a good length, outside off. Gill defends it out.
On off, kept out by Gill.
A couple more but slightly streaky! Full again, on off. Shubman Gill looks to drive but the ball takes the outer half of the bat towards deep point. The batters take a couple of runs.
FOUR! Gill loves to play on the leg side! This was fuller in length, on the pads. Shubman Gill clears his front leg and flicks it to deep square leg for a boundary.
Length ball, on middle, coming back in. Shubman Gill covers the line and defends it on the leg side.
Short and turning away, outside off. Pujara cuts but finds the cover fielder.
Loopy ball, around off. Cheteshwar Pujara punches it back to the bowler off the back foot. Ajaz Patel is not allowing Pujara to make use of his feet.
On off, pushed back to the bowler.
Floats it up, on middle. Pujara defends it off the front foot.
Slower through the air, on leg. Pujara blocks it out.
Tosses it up, on middle. Pujara rocks back and knocks it back to the bowler.

DRINKS! Kyle Jamieson has been excellent with the ball and was rewarded with the wicket of Mayank Agarwal. Since then, Shubman Gill and Cheteshwar Pujara have done to battle out the Kiwi bowlers. They will look to continue to bat till lunch now.
On a good length, around off, nipping back in. Shubman Gill leaves it untouched.
Full and well outside off, left alone by Gill.
Outside off, pushed past point for a run.
On a good length, on middle. Pujara nudges it to mid-wicket.
On a length, outside off, nipping away. Shubman Gill opens the face of the bat and drives it through covers. Only for a single though.
Tim Southee (3-0-12-0) is back into the attack.
Length ball, on middle. Gill hits it on the leg side.
Loopy ball, on leg. Pujara dances down the track and defends it out watchfully to the off side. A maiden for Ajaz Patel.
Pushed wider and quicker, Pujara lets it be.
On middle, clipped to square leg.
Slower through the air, on off. Pujara defends it out.
Full and on off, Pujara steps out and nudges it to mid-wicket.
Loopy ball, on off. Pujara defends it off the front foot.
Full and on middle, Pujara clips it to backward square leg. He retains the strike by picking up a single.
On a length, around off, shapes away a little late. Cheteshwar Pujara leaves it alone.
Fuller in length, on off. Pujara pushes it to mid on.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Cheteshwar Pujara clips it behind square on the leg side for a couple of runs.
Good-length ball, on middle. Pujara shuffles a bit and defends it down the track.
On a good length, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara defends it right under his eyes.
On off, Gill defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Cut away! Tosses it up, on off. Shubman Gill hangs back and cuts it through point to collect a boundary. Excellent placement from the youngster this time. Gets his first boundary of the day.
Slower through the air, around middle. Shubman Gill hangs back and punches it past the bowler for a couple of runs.
Loopy ball, on leg. Pujara plays it to wide of mid on for a run.
Full again, on leg. Pujara again steps out and flicks it to mid on.
Full and on leg, Cheteshwar Pujara uses his feet and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Another maiden for Kyle Jamieson! Length ball, on off. Shubman Gill pushes it towards point.
Good-length ball, outside off. Gill is not interested to offer a shot on that one.
Similar line and length, outside off. Shubman Gill lets it sail through.
Good-length ball, outside off, nipping away a bit. Shubman Gill leaves it alone.
Tad fuller, outside off. Shubman Gill watches the ball closely and lets it go.
Length ball down the leg side, Shubman Gill looks to flick but misses. Tom Blundell does well to move to his right and collect the ball.
On middle, Cheteshwar Pujara knocks this to the leg side.
Floated around off again, punched to the cover region.
Fuller, angling in, around off, easily defended by Pujara.
On middle, worked wide of the mid on fielder, where William Somerville dives to his right and half-stops the ball. One run only.
Touch shorter, on the pads, nicely clipped through mid-wicket for a brace.
Floated, around off, eased to mid off now.
Fuller, around off, Pujara blocks this out to the off side. An excellent over by Kyle!
Cheteshwar Pujara walks out to bat at No.3.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Mayank Agarwal departs and the Kiwis have drawn first blood early in the morning session. Kyle Jamieson has been probing and making life difficult for the Indian openers and he reaps rewards for his hard work here. Can't say that he hasn't deserved this honestly. He keeps pushing with the same line and length and gets rid of Agarwal. Back-of-a-length delivery again, on the fourth stump line, the ball lands and curls away. Mayank Agarwal, like he has been all morning, looks for the tentative poke but only manages a thin feather, which is gobbled up by Tom Blundell behind the sticks. Agarwal has a chat with Gill but he opts not to take the review.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: On middle, glanced to the leg side this time.

FOUR! Crunched. Agarwal gets the first boundary of the game. Kyle Jamieson goes fuller this time, outside off, Mayank Agarwal leans ahead and creams this one through covers. Nobody was going to stop that.

Peach! What a delivery. Fantastic bowling. Hits the deck hard around off, the ball lands and shapes away now, Mayank Agarwal is gentle as he looks to have a poke at this but the ball whistles past his blade to the keeper.
A bumper this time, around off and middle, takes Mayank by surprise but he does well to duck down.
This one stays low now! Around off, slightly shorter, Shubman goes back to play it and the ball stays a touch low. He adjusts well and fends this one out.

Slightly shorter, around off, Shubman Gill skips down and looks to play this but misses. Gets pinged on the pad and an appeal is made but this does not look like it would be out. The umpire does not flinch too.
On middle now, worked gently to the mid on fielder.
Fuller, on off, pushed to covers.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.

Spin straightaway for Patel! He floats this one up, fuller, around off, the ball lands and turns away slightly as Gill looks to defend, but the ball catches the outside edge and bounces away from the slip fielder.
First change of the morning. Ajaz Patel is brought into the attack. He replaces Tim Southee.
Quick single. On a length on off, worked to covers and the batters scamper through for one. There is an overthrow too but the batters do not go for the second.
Shubman pushes this to the fielder at covers now.
Outside off, no shot offered now.
Well bowled again. Moving away on a length outside off, Gill looks to push this through the off side but this curves away from the right-hander, to the keeper.
NO BALL! Angled into the middle pole again, this is nudged to the leg side. Kyle oversteps by a huge margin and hence, another no ball has been called.
On middle, kept out.
Outside off, pushed away to point.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.

EDGY FOUR! The edge is induced but it runs away to the boundary ropes. Around off, on a length, going away this time, Mayank Agarwal has a tentative poke at this and the ball takes the outside edge, bounces in between the keeper and first slip and runs away to the ropes.
Good length, in the fourth stump channel, nipping away, easy leave again for Mayank.
Short of a length, around off, Mayank shuffles and taps this to the off side.
Outside off, on a length, Mayank misses his poke here.

Good running from this duo. Slightly fuller, outside off, Shubman Gill leans ahead and creams this one through the covers. They take two and notice that there is a bit of misfield and hence, they return for the third too.
An action replay of the previous delivery. Outside off, fuller, no shot offered by Mayank this time.
Wider outside off, an easy leave for Mayank.
A touch fuller this time, outside off, a gentle push by Mayank Agarwal through covers and the batters complete the second run with ease.
NO BALL! Angled into middle and leg pole, pushed away to the left of mid on, who runs across and stops the ball. Kyle Jamieson has overstepped and hence, a no ball has been called.
Around off, on a length, Mayank hits this towards the cover region.
Around off, poked away to the slip cordon.
Jamieson is making the ball talk here! Again there is movement. On the fourth stump line, on a good length, the ball swirls away as Mayank Agarwal misses his attempted defense.
Angled into the pads this time, Gill closes the face of this blade and knocks this through mid-wicket. He collects two runs and opens his account too.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Around off, Gill walks down and taps this to mid on. Wants one but is sent back now.
Shubman Gill has taken a review for LBW. There is a clear inside edge onto the pads. No need for UltraEdge on this one. The on-field decision has been reversed. India retain their review.

NOT OUT! Clearly not out as there was bat on this. The on-field called has been reversed here. Southee serves a back-of-a-length delivery, around off, coming in slightly as Gill looks to defend. He seems to have missed it as he gets hit on the pads. An excited appeal from the Kiwis and the finger has been raised. Gill goes for the review straightaway. As soon as replays roll in, you know why he was so confident. A clear inside edge, onto the pad. Gill continues on.
This is slipped down the leg side, Shubman misses his flick this time.
Outside off on a length, Gill watches it sway away and leaves it alone.
Good length, on off, pushed to covers. A maiden to begin for Kyle Jamieson!
Slightly closer to the off pole, on a length, but still not enough for Mayank to play at this. He makes another leave.
Easy leave. A touch fuller, outside off, moving away now, left alone easily.
Trying to bowl the inswinger this time. Short of a length, way outside off, the ball lands and nips in gently as Mayank defends inside the line and misses.

Play and a miss! What a curler from Jamieson. This time the line is better, on the fifth stump channel, on a fuller length, the ball lands and curls away as Mayank Agarwal looks to drive. The ball whiskers past the blade to the keeper.
Kyle Jamieson starts with a fuller delivery, way outside off, there is away movement too as Mayank just leaves this one be.
Kyle Jamieson to bowl from the opposite end.
On a length around off, Gill blocks this one out. A tidy start from Southee.
Good-length ball this time, around off, it is played through cover-point and the strike is rotated with a run now.
Around off, on a length now, Mayank pokes this one and finds the third slip fielder on the bounce.

India and Mayank Agarwal open their account here as the crowds cheer on. Outside off this time, back of a length, the ball seams away slightly again as Agarwal pushes this one past point and the batters complete two this time.
Similar line and length this time, this time it is closer to Mayank, who defends this one out.

Right on the money is Tim Southee on ball one! He starts with a slightly back-of-a-length delivery, around off, there is a slight bit of away movement as Agarwal gently pokes this one away to the point region.

Done with the pre-match formalities! Now, New Zealand players make their way into the middle and take their respective fielding positions. The Indian openers - Shubman Gill and Mayank Agarwal stride out to the middle as well. Kane Williamson hands the red cherry to Tim Southee. He will start the proceedings with the ball. Here we go...
We are set to begin but before that, both the teams line up for their respective national anthems. First it will be New Zealand's followed by India's.

Cheteshwar Pujara is in for a chat! He says that it is an honor to be part of this team and he is looking forward to being the vice captain. Says that he was part of the Indian T20 League and he was training and batting and he has prepared well and they are looking forward to playing at home. Says that this is an opportunity for the younger players and they have to also play with responsibility. Tells that there was low bounce the last time they played here but you never know as they are playing here after 3-4 years.

Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham, Will Young, Kane Williamson (C), Ross Taylor, Henry Nicholls, Tom Blundell (WK), Rachin Ravindra (DEBUT), Tim Southee, Ajaz Patel, Kyle Jamieson, William Somerville.

India (Playing XI) - Mayank Agarwal, Shubman Gill, Cheteshwar Pujara, Ajinkya Rahane (C), Shreyas Iyer (DEBUT), Wriddhiman Saha (WK), Ravindra Jadeja, Axar Patel, Ravichandran Ashwin, Ishant Sharma, Umesh Yadav.

Kane Williamson, the New Zealand captain, says that they would have batted first too but they have the ball in hand and they will look to make a few breakthroughs early on. Adds that this is a different challenge and they are not looking back and are looking ahead right now. Tells us that his elbow is alright. Kane says that they have to make a couple of changes to their side keeping in mind that they need to have spinners in their ranks. Informs that they are going with two pacers, two spinners, and a spinning allrounder.

Ajinkya Rahane, the skipper of India says that they will bat first. Mentions that the surface looks really good. Tells that it is an opportunity for everyone to do well and then head to Mumbai. Tells that they are excited to play under the new coaching staff and are looking forward to playing under Rahul Dravid. Tells that New Zealand plays as a unit and are a quality side and are not going to take them lightly. Informs that Shreyas Iyer is set to make his debut and they are going with 3 spinners and 2 seamers.
TOSS - Ajinkya Rahane and Kane Williamson have made their way out into the middle now. Rahane flips and tails is what Kane calls but it lands heads. INDIA HAVE ELECTED TO BAT FIRST!

Pitch Report - Simon Doull and Deep Dasgupta are near the pitch. Doull says that there are some cracks already opening up. Says that it is a beautiful batting pitch and the spinners might get some turn early on. Dasgupta mentions that the batters will have to work hard to get runs. Doull tells the first and the last hour will be crucial as usual but once the light comes on, the ball might behave differently. Also says that reverse swing is expected.
Update - The news from the middle is that Shreyas Iyer is set to make his Test debut. He receives the cap from one of India's greatest, Sunil Gavaskar.

The Kiwis have held the wooden spoon over India on multiple occasions in all formats of the ICC tournaments over the last couple of years and will be confident heading into this series too. They have a strong core of players and Williamson too is back to lead his lads. It will be interesting to see how the Kiwis face the turning tracks on these Indian decks. Their bowling combination will be one to look at as well as it will be exciting to see how many pacers make the cut and how many spinners they go with. The Black Caps will want to continue their tradition of beating India and looking at this slightly depleted Indian team, it could be a possibility. All-in-all, this game is not one to be missed. Let's hope for a close one. Stay tuned as we bring you more updates....

Talking about India first, their start in the new WTC cycle has been nothing short of phenomenal as after their disappointment due to the loss in the WTC final against the Black Caps, they came out hammer and tongs and were in supreme form against England, in the Brits' backyard and the Indians would want to continue the same. They will be without their two main protagonists, both their openers, as Rohit Sharma is resting for this series and KL Rahul is out injured and their services will be missed the most. Pant and Bumrah will be sitting this series out too and we should see some changes to the XI. Since Kohli is missing this Test alone and coming back for the next, Rahane will be leading the hosts on the field. Shreyas Iyer could be the player to make his international debut in this format for the Indians, slotting into that number 4 position. Will Saha or Bharat play? Will Jadeja, Axar, and Ashwin all play? Who will partner Agarwal at the top? The picture will become more clearer come the toss...

Hello, folks! Time for you to ditch your colorful jerseys and don the white as Test cricket is back!!! It has been a while since we have been focussing on the shortest format of the game, but now, we return to the longest format as Test cricket is here! The two finalists of the 2019–2021 ICC World Test Championship, India and New Zealand are locking horns for a 2-game Test series and it is building up to be an exciting one. On that note, welcome to the coverage.
... Match Day ...
We are back for India's second innings! Mayank Agarwal and Shubman Gill walk out to bat. Tim Southee will start with the ball.

Now, there is still time for some play left on Day 3. India will have to come out to play around 4 overs. It is called the nervy period and they will dearly hope they can get through this unscathed. New Zealand on the other hand, will love a wicket at least. An interesting phase awaits.

New Zealand would not want to look at their scorecard! Expect for the top two, there was hardly any contribution from the rest. When the day started, they would have probably been thinking about taking a lead but after the openers, Tom Latham and Will Young, just the one batter managed to cross the 20-run mark. Latham and Young though were exceptional, the two were very unfortunate to not get to their ton. Had it not been for them, the Kiwis would have probably fallen another 100 short of India's total.

It was Ravichandran Ashwin though who started things off as he got Will Young early and since then, the Kiwis kept losing wickets at regular intervals. The spinners wreaked havoc as the three got 9 between them, with Axar Patel getting a 5-wicket haul. Umesh got 1 and that too the important one of Kane Williamson. From 151 for 0, they have managed to bowl the visitors out for under 300 which is an amazing effort.

An excellent effort with the ball by the Indian bowling attack! Whereas, the Kiwis will be mighty disappointed with their effort with the bat. They have fallen 49 runs short of India's score and 49 runs in Indian conditions by no means is a small lead. It is Axar Patel who leads the team off the field and rightly so, he was the pick with yet another fifer to his name.

We are back! It is the final session of the day. The over-rate for India has been decent so just the 31 overs left. Tom Blundell and Kyle Jamieson will continue their innings. Jadeja to begin. Here we go...
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

For New Zealand, the middle order was a disappointment. Nobody managed to cross the 20-run mark and they are now in danger of not wiping off the deficit. Tom Blundell is the last recognized batter, Kyle Jamieson can bat but not a lot left after this. The Kiwis will hope the two can somehow stitch a good stand and hope they can get close to the Indian total. Will we see a more attacking approach by them or will they continue to play like they have? Do join us at 2:35 pm Local (9:05 am GMT) to find out.

The two left-arm spinners came to the party! More than Ravindra Jadeja it was the Axar Patel show in this session. He picked three out of the 4 to fall and they were three big wickets. Jadeja then got rid of Rachin Ravindra to push the Kiwis more onto the back foot. The other Indian bowlers also played their part as they did not let the runs flow and kept building the pressure. India still lead by a margin of 96 runs and they would want to take the remaining wickets quickly in the last session.

End of a really good session for India! 4 wickets is what they have managed to pick and New Zealand find themselves in trouble despite being in a good position entering the afternoon session. This was the issue for them with the pace they were going at. Despite the big opening stand, India were always well and truly in the game as they always kept the Kiwis in check. Also, with the wicket deteriorating, batting was going to get tougher and the Indian spinners were going to come into play and that is what happened

The game still pretty much hangs in balance. India did take two big wickets but New Zealand have slowly, yet steadily, brought down the deficit to under 150. If the next batter puts on a good stand with Latham, the Kiwis would be well on track to put on a lead of their own. A lot will defend on how the batters fare against the new ball in the next session. An exciting session awaits us post Lunch. Do join us for the same at 12:10 pm Local (6:40 am GMT) for the same!

A brilliant session of Test cricket between these two sides. Will Young did not last long as Ravichandran Ashwin got the better of him. Ashwin was sensational with the ball for India. He used the angles well, varied his pace, changed his follow-through in an attempt to get the second wicket for India. He did get past the outside edge on multiple occasions and troubled the batters but could not get the wicket. Tom Latham and Kane Williamson were batting quite well and had stitched a good stand but Umesh Yadav struck just before Lunch with the second new ball and sent back the Kiwi skipper.

India struck gold right before Lunch and that has titled the session in their favour. It was a hard-fought session of Test cricket with both the sides not giving the other an inch but the wicket of Kane Williamson right before the end of the session would mean that India have the advantage here.

We are set to get underway! India and the Kiwi openers, Tom Latham and Will Young, have made their way out to the middle. Wriddhiman Saha has some issues with the neck so Srikar Bharat is keeping the wickets for India. Ishant Sharma is set to start with the ball.

Ishant Sharma is down for a chat. He says the first hour will be important but given how old the ball is, he can't say how it will behave. Adds that he doesn't expect a lot of reverse swing and would just go straight, but emphasizes that he can't say for sure. Cheekily confesses that pacers in India usually do the job of containment and let the spinners take the wickets.

Pitch Report - Ajit Agarkar is down for the pitch report. He says that the pitch looks still very good to bat on. Adds that there was a bit more spin towards the end of Day 2 but it is quite slow still. Deep Dasgupta says that the rough patches are getting rougher as the game goes on but the slow nature of the pitch will make it easier for the batters.

Day 2 was all about the Kiwis. First, Tim Southee ran through India's middle order to make sure that the hosts do not put on a massive total on the board. Then, Will Young and Tom Latham put on a brilliant show with the bat. Not losing a single wicket on Day 2 was exactly what they would have wanted in these conditions. The pitch was good quite to bat but towards the end of the day, it started showing a few more tricks. How the first hour of Day 3 goes will play a crucial role here. The hosts would look to pick up a couple of wickets while the Kiwis would want these two batters to bat out this session too.

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 3 of this Test between India and New Zealand. We have an exciting day of Test cricket coming up with the game nicely poised and no team having too big of an advantage at this moment. What happens in the next three sessions will play a big role in determining which way this match goes. With that, we once again welcome to our coverage.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then! A fantastic day of Test cricket for New Zealand. Not so much for India. Still, there is plenty of time left in the Test and anything can happen. Day 3 is termed the moving day and it surely promises to be a cracking day. Do join us on 27th November at 9:30 am Local (4 am GMT) to find out what happens on Day 3. Cheers!

The centurion, Shreyas Iyer, is down for a chat. Iyer says he was delighted with how things went for him but he could not get good sleep, he thought he would sleep well but that was not the case. Adds that Sunil Gavaskar motivated him and asked him to stay in the present and not think of what will happen too far ahead. On being asked by Sunil Gavaskar as to why is he wearing a hat and not the cap given by him, Iyer jokes it was too sunny that is why! Mentions it was a harsh sleep last night but the century made him feel great. Ends by saying the wicket looks flat but the cracks are opening up and he hopes they do not concede a lot of runs.

A tough day for the hosts. In the first session, they lost their middle order and did not get as many runs as they would have liked. India were bundled out right after the Lunch break and the total was under 350. They would have wanted to take early wickets but that did not happen. The pitch was a good one to bat on and there was not much assistance for the bowlers. The bowlers bowled well but nothing went their way. But at the fag end of the day, the pitch was showing a few more tricks as there was a bit more grip and the odd ball was staying low. They would want to capitalize on that and take early wickets on Day 3.

A really, really good effort by the New Zealand openers. They were quite watchful to start with and once they had their eyes in, both of them started scoring more freely. Will Young got more boundaries than Tom Latham but both got their fifties and would want to extend their stand even further on Day 3. Earlier in the day though, the star for New Zealand was Tim Southee. India were in a good position at the start of Day 2 but Southee bowled brilliantly in the morning session to rock the Indian middle order. He ended with a 5-wicket haul and put New Zealand in a good position.

Bad light! The light has been offered to the Kiwis and they take it. That will be the end of Day 2 and New Zealand will be very, very happy with how things have panned out for them on the second day. No doubt whatsoever that they won each and every session on Day 2.
