Outside off, left alone.
On middle, defended.
Well bowled! Sees Latham come down the track and bowls it wide outside off, Latham pushes it to covers.
On the pads, Young sweeps but to square leg.
On middle, Young defends it onto the ground.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
That might have hurt! On off, Latham sweeps, it hits the man at short leg.
On middle, defended.
Half a chance! Down the leg side, Latham flicks it, Saha moves well down the leg side but it hits the glove and goes down to the fine leg region for two.
Flatter and outside off, Young guides it to point.
On off, Young plays it to covers.
On the stumps, Young plays it back to the bowler.
Another one floated up on off, defended.
Floats it up on middle, Young keeps it out with ease.
Tossed up on off, blocked.
Floats it up on off, this is driven back to the bowler who tries to stop it but lets it through. A run taken.
On off, blocked.
That drifts in with the angle from outside off, it is guided to point.
Another one on the stumps, kept out.
On middle, defended.

A chat between Ashwin and the umpire. Actually, Mayank Agarwal is the man at gully. He moved just before the ball was bowled and that prompted the umpire to have a word with Ashwin. Mayank Agarwal is sitting on his knees at gully. Interesting fielding position.
Angled into the pads, stays low. Young looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
On the pads and worked past mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

Just short of the fielder! Loopy ball, outside off. Latham comes forward to defend but gets the outside edge. The ball lands short of the man at first slip. Some encouraging signs for India in the last few overs.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out towards the bowler.
Nicely flighted, outside off. Latham pushes it towards backward point.
Flatter and outside off. Latham shuffles across and taps it to cover.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on off. Young is solid in his defense.
Flatter and on middle. Young blocks it from the crease.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed to cover.
WOW! Tossed up, on off. Young comes forward to block but the ball turns away and goes past the outside edge and just past the off pole. Patel would like to do that once again.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Great use of the feet! Young dances down the track, gets to the pitch of the ball and drives it past cover for a boundary.
Darted on middle. :Latham works it to the leg side.
Latham comes forward to block it.
That has spun sharply! Tossed up, this lands in the rough and turns viciously. Latham looks to drive but gets no bat on it. Rahane dives to his right at first slip and gets his hands to it.
Loopy ball, outside off. Latham looks to sweep but the ball  goes just past the off pole.
Loopy ball, around off. Latham blocks it out.
Shorter ball, around off. Latham punches it to cover.

DRINKS! The Kiwis continue to do well after Tea! Young and Latham have crossed the 100-run mark but there is still a long way to go. Their aim would be to end the day without losing a wicket. India on the other hand, will be desperate to break this stand. Do they have a hero in them? We will find out.
Full ball, on off. Young blocks it off the front foot.
Darted on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, outside off. Latham pushes it past cover for one.
Shorter ball, around off. Latham blocks it from the crease.
Darted on the pads. Worked towards short leg.
Latham comes down the track and pushes it to mid-wicket.
Axar Patel comes on now.
Loopy ball, on off. Young blocks it nicely under his eyes.
Full ball, on the pads. Latham works it to deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Loopy ball, on the pads. Latham tickles it fine to the fine leg fence.
Darted on the pads. Worked to mid-wicket.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Young works it past square leg for one.
Shorter ball, on off. Pushed to mid on.
Loopy ball, on middle and leg. Latham works it to the leg side.
Quick single! Full ball, on off. Young drives it towards mid off and takes off for a single.
Darted on the pads. Young blocks it to the leg side.
Loopy ball, around off. Blocked out.
Tossed up, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Fuller ball, on middle. Young works it towards mid on. But the fielder gets across and cuts it off.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Latham blocks it to the leg side.
Young comes down the track and works it to long on for one.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
Nicely tossed up, on off. Young blocks it well.
Loopy ball, around off. Young blocks it off the front foor.
Shorter ball, around off. Young pushes it to mid on.
Shorter ball, outside off. Latham goes back and pushes it to covers.
Loopy ball, on off. Latham blocks it off the front foot.
Fuller ball, on off. Latham defends it off the front foot.
FOUR! Top shot by Tom Latham! Tossed up, on off. Latham gets low and sweeps it hard to the mid-wicket fence.
Shorter ball, around off. Latham blocks it from the back foot.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Latham works it back to the bowler.
Full ball, on the pads. Young works it towards mid-wicket.
Fuller ball, around off. Young comes forward and blocks it to mid off.
Short of a length, outside off. Latham works it past mid-wicket for one.
Short of a length, outside off. Tapped towards the slip cordon.
Length ball, around off. Young pushes it past covers for one. No ball called as the bowler has overstepped.
Length ball, on off. Latham comes forward and blocks it to mid off.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.

Slows it up a little and lands it on middle, Young shows the full face of the bat and plays it back to the bowler. Jadeja is accurately hitting the right line and looking for some turn but there are hardly any balls which have misbehaved.
On middle, Young prods forward and plays it back to the bowler.
Once again makes the batter play, Young easily blocks.
On the stumps yet again. Young plays it towards point.
On off, this is pushed to coves.
Flatter and on middle, defended.
On middle, kept out.
Outside off, not played at.
Lovely! Angles this in from around the wicket, gets it to land it on off and then move away. Latham looks to drive but is beaten. Trademark Ishant Sharma there.
This is well wide outside off, Latham leaves it alone.
Outside off and fuller, this is driven but to point.
Good length and on middle, blocked.
Change. Ishant Sharma (4-2-6-0) is back on.

FOUR! Edgy! Need a little luck on such pitches! Outside off, this one stays low. Young looks to push it through the off side but it goes off the bottom, between the legs of the keeper and down to the third man fence.
On middle, defended.
Review time! India have reviewed this for LBW. No bat on that one. But, it is missing the wickets! India lose a review.

NOT OUT! That is missing the leg pole! Did not see that coming! Initially we thought there was bat. Really good decision. This is on middle, Young looks to play the paddle sweep but seems to have missed it. It hits the pad and goes behind. Young is not sure about where the ball is and takes off. It rolls just behind the keeper. Latham asks him to go back and Young does so. He puts in a dive to get in and the throw is also a wide one. The appeal from the Indians in the meantime is turned down. Rahane reviews. Replays show that it is going down with the angle.
On middle, Young defends it.
Shorter and on off, Young pushes it to covers.
Fires it on middle, looking for some turn away. This goes on with the arm. Blocked.
A dot to end! On off, Latham guides it to point.
From around the wicket, angles it into the middle pole, Latham plays it back to the bowler. There seems nothing in the wicket for the pacers.
India have some issues with the ball. The umpire brings out the gauge to check the shape but it is fine.
Slightly fuller in length and on middle, Latham drives it nicely but finds mid off.
Makes the batter play yet again by bowling it on middle, Latham negotiates it easily.
On off, it is pushed to covers.
On middle, kept out.
Fires this one in on middle, Young plays it off the back foot.
Around middle, defended nicely this time.

What a beauty! Wow! Unplayable! All you can do is hope, it misses the outside edge and the off pole. First ball which probably turned from the line of the stumps. It lands on off, Young lunges and looks to defend. This one spins square, past the outside edge and the off pole. This will cause doubts in the batter's mind now. However, it is mostly the balls which slide on that get you and not the ones which turn.
On middle, blocked.
Fired into the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Latham once again plays the sweep, it goes through square leg for one.
Yet another dot! On middle, Young keeps it out.
Another one on a length and around middle, defended.
Very solid! Length and on middle, Young gets right behind the line of the ball and defends.
A little too straight this time, this is clipped through square leg for one.
In the air... safe! Good length and on off, this lands and then jags back in. Latham looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. It lobs on the leg side but safe.
Length and on off, Latham is solid in defense.
Fires it on the stumps, Young hangs back and plays it onto the ground.
Flatter and on middle, comes slow off the surface. Blocked.
On middle, Young lunges and keeps it out.
Flatter and on off, defended.
Sweeps and it goes through square leg for one.
Comes down the track and then works it straight to mid-wicket. He takes off for a run, not sure where Latham is going, realizes there is no run and heads back.
FOUR! Short of a length, outside off. Young punches it past covers for a boundary. He is batting really well out in the middle.
FOUR! Length ball, around off. Young looks to block but gets the outside edge. It runs to the fence.
Full ball, on the pads. Young looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
Length ball, on the pads. Latham works it past mid-wicket for one.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
Length ball, outside off. Latham looks to drive but gets the inside edge on the pads.
Loopy ball, on off. Young gets forward to block it.
Darted on off. Young goes back to block but the ball stays a bit low and he gets an inside edge on the pads.
Flatter ball, on off. Pushed back to the bowler.
Loopy ball, on off. Young blocks it off the front foot.
Darted on the pads. Worked to fine leg for one.
Loopy ball, outside off. Latham looks to paddle but gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but the impact is outside off.
Full ball, on the pads. Young taps it to the leg side.
Slower ball this time by Yadav. This is fuller and on off. But Young picks it up early and blocks it.
Length ball, on off. Young blocks it from the crease.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.

FOUR! FIFTY FOR YOUNG! What an innings he has played and he would want to convert this into a ton. Length ball, outside off. Young looks to defend with soft hands. The ball takes the outside edge and runs past gully for a boundary.
Length ball, down the leg side. Young misses the flick but Saha goes well to dive and gather it.
Umesh Yadav to start from the other end.
Darted on middle. Latham works it to mid-wicket.
Shorter ball, outside off. Latham leaves it alone.
Shorter ball, on the pads. Worked to mid-wicket.
Loopy ball, outside off. Latham goes for the sweep but gets hit on the pads. The impact is outside off though.
Tossed up, around off. Latham comes down the track and pushes it down the ground.
Fuller ball, around off. Blocked out.

Welcome back to the final session of the day! Ajinkya Rahane has a few words to say to his team before they spread out on the field. Tom Latham and Will Young walk out to bat. Ravindra Jadeja to start the session.
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

India, on the other hand, just have to be patient. There is not a lot of assistance for them as of yet but the wicket is slowly starting to play its tricks. They would love to get a wicket though after the break. An important session awaits. Do join us for the same at 2:30 pm Local (9 am GMT). Meanwhile, we too will grab a cub of tea!

First, the Kiwis managed to take the two wickets remaining in no time and keep India under 350 and then have gone through the remaining part unscathed. Both, Tom Latham and Will Young, took their own time to start with but as the game progressed, got more and more confident and have then started to score freely. They are set and the Kiwis will hope they can cash in.
Solid, solid show from the Kiwi openers! It was very important for them to get a good start and the openers have been brilliant so far. Quite easily this session has belonged to the visitors.

FOUR! What a shot to end the session and New Zealand would be very happy! Full ball, outside off. Young drives it gloriously. The man at short cover dives but has no chance. The ball runs to the fence and that is Tea on Day 2!
Shorter again, but punched back to the bowler.
Quicker ball, around off. Pushed to cover.
Patel bowls it shorter this time, on off. Young plays it with soft hands.
Latham comes down the track, pushes it to mid on and takes off for a single.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Young is looking really good in the middle! A touch fuller, outside off. He gets under the ball, extends his arms and hits it wide of mid off for a boundary.
Darted on the pads. Young taps it towards short leg.
On middle this time but Young blocks this well.
Tossed up, around off. Young gets forward and blocks it.
Fuller ball, on off. Latham gets low and sweeps it to deep square leg for one.
Shorter ball, outside off. Latham blocks it with soft hands.
Shorter ball, outside off. Worked past mid-wicket for one.
FOUR! Well played! Angled into the pads. Young clips it past short fine leg. Ashwin chases it but the ball wins the race.
On the pads. Latham works it past short leg and gets a single.
Full this time, on off. Latham blocks it.
Loopy ball, on off. Latham paddles it towards fine leg for a couple of runs.
Loopy ball, on off. Blocked out.
Change. Axar Patel is brought on now.
Shorter this time, outside off. Young gets the outer half of the bat towards backward point.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
Stays low! Darted on the pads. It stays low and beats Young's attempted flick. There is an appeal for LBW but the ball is heading down the leg pole.
Full ball, outside off. Young nicely drives it to short cover.
Loopy ball, outside off. Pushed to the off side.
Darted on middle. Young blocks it.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Latham blocks it out towards the bowler.
Shorter and quicker, outside off. Latham covers the stumps and blocks it.
Now, he pushes it towards mid off.
A solid defensive push towards mid on.
Quicker ball, on the pads. Latham taps it to the leg side.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on off. Latham comes down the track and works it to mid on. They sprint for a quick single.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Lovely stroke by Latham! He does play that stroke really well. He sweeps this from way outside off and finds the square leg fence.
Full ball, on the pads. Young works it past square leg for one.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out. No ball called as Jadeja has overstepped.
Kept too low! This lands outside off and does not rise up at all. Young looks to push it but gets no bat on it. Saha does well to gather it though.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
Full ball, on the pads. Young works it past square leg and gets a single.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Quality stroke by Young! This is tossed up nicely, outside off. He comes down the track and hits it over Ashwin's head and gets a boundary.
Fuller this time, on middle. Bit of spin but Young has no problems in defending it.
Nicely done! Loopy ball, on off. Young gets low and paddles it towards fine leg for a couple.
On the pads. Latham works it past square leg and gets one.
Darted on the pads this time. Young flicks it but straight towards short leg.
Shorter ball, around off. Young punches it to cover.
Darted on middle. Latham sweeps it past square leg and gets a single.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
Darted on the pads. Young flicks it past square leg and gets a single.
Shorter ball, on off. Young goes back and works it towards mid-wicket.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out with ease. Both these batters are looking quite comfortable against the spinners.
Loopy ball, around off. Latham gets the inside edge on the pads while looking to block.
A single as this is worked down to long on.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
Young puts in a stride to block this one.
Darted down the leg side. Latham works it towards fine leg and gets a single.
Nicely tossed up, on middle. There is a bit of turn on it but Young blocks it with ease.
Full again, outside off. Young pushes it to cover.
Darted on the pads. Worked to the leg side.
Flatter ball, around off. Pushed back towards Jadeja.
Fuller ball, on middle and leg. Young blocks it out.
Darted on the pads. Blocked out.
Fuller ball, on off. Young works it past square leg and gets a single.
Pushed to the off side this time.
Nicely tossed up, on off. Young gets forward and blocks it.
Flatter ball, outside off. Young looks to block but is beaten.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out by Young.
Tossed up, around off. Blocked out.
UDRS time! Latham has reviewed this LBW decision. Again, he has gotten an inside edge on it!

NOT OUT! There is a big inside edge and Latham survives again! This lands outside off and spins back in sharply. Latham goes back and tries to push it through the off side but he gets an inside edge onto the pads. An appeal and the finger is raised. He reviews straightaway and replays show that there is an inside edge.
On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Shorter and on off, this is pushed to covers.
On middle, defended.
NOT OUT! On off, this is pushed to covers. They go for one. The fielder picks the ball up and has a shy at the bowler's end. He hits. It is referred but replays show that Latham is well in.
Is that a run out? Nope, the batter is well in.
A huge appeal but turned down! This lands outside off, Latham plants his front foot outside the line and tries to sweep but misses to get hit on the pads.
Ravindra Jadeja is set to bowl now.
On the pads, Latham looks to work it on the leg side but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A single taken. Leg bye.
Conitnues to attack the stumps, Latham negotiates it with ease.
On middle, kept out.
Loopy ball and on middle, defended.
Flatter and on middle, it is worked through mid-wicket for one.
FOUR! good shot! Young gets down on one knee, this is on the pads, he sweeps it over backward square leg for a boundary.
On off, Latham strokes it to covers.
On the stumps, Latham gets right behind the line and defends.
Another one on a length and on off, blocked again.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed to covers.
Good length and on off, Young plays it late and towards point for one.
On middle, kept out.
The straigther one, it lands on off and goes on with the angle. Young looks to defend but it goes off the outside edge through point for three.
Another one on middle, defended.
Floats it up and lands it on off, blocked.
Another one floated up on middle, Young looks to defend but it goes off the inner half towards square leg.
Tossed up on off, defended.

Drinks! A solid start by the Kiwi openers so far. They have been solid with their technique and would now look to score more freely now. The Indian bowlers have bowled in the right channels but their wait for the first wicket continues. Patience is the name of the game, for both the sides.
On middle, Latham gets behind the line and keeps it out.
Length again and on off, it is pushed to covers.
On middle, defended.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
FOUR! EDGY! Length and on off, shapes away a touch. Young looks to defend, he does so with soft hands, it goes off the outside edge down to the third man fence.
On middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Close! Shortish and outside off, holds in the surface a touch. Latham looks to push at it but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Flatter and on middle, Latham hangs back and defends.
On middle, Young works it through mid-wicket for one.
Gives it air and lands it on off, Young lunges and defends.
Three! Flatter and on middle, this one stays a touch low. Latham works it through square leg for three.
A loose delivery! Down the leg side, Latham looks to sweep but misses.
A leave to end the over as this is bowled outside off.
Lovely shot but to no avail! Fuller and on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Another one on a length and around off, blocked. There was extra bounce there, Young played it well by taking  a hand off the handle.
Attacks the stumps this time, Young defends.
Good length, corrects his line, bowls it outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Whipped away! That should make Young feel good! It is a half volley, on the pads, this is worked through square leg for a boundary.
Tossed up again, gets it to land on middle, defended again. Good start by Ashwin. Not a lot of turn for him but the pace he bowled at was very good.
Slower through the air and on middle, blocked.
Edgy run! Flatter and on off, Young goes back and looks to defend, it goes off the outer half towards short third man for one.
Had there been a direct hit, Latham could have been in trouble! On middle, this is worked to square leg. They go for one. Ishant gets to the ball and has a shy at the bowler's end but misses.
Tosses it up this time and lands it on middle, defended again.
Flatter and on off, Latham works it to mid on.
Change. Time for some spin as Ravichandran Ashwin is set to roll his arm over.
That is a beauty! This starts on off and then shapes away late. Young is beaten as he tries to block.
Young misses out! This is on his pads, Young looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and Saha dives to his left to stop it.
Solid! Good length and on off, Young keeps it out.
Another one on a length and outside off, not played at.
Outside off, left alone.
On off, defended.

Length ball, angling down the leg side. Latham looks to flick but misses. Saha dives to his right and gathers the ball. There is definitely some deflection and Saha thinks that it hit the bat. The appeal is turned down though. Rahane has a word with Yadav, who suggests that it hit the pads. No review is taken.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed to covers.
Rapped on the pads! Length ball, lands outside off and comes back with the angle. Latham comes forward to block but gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but turned down.
Fuller ball, on off. Latham comes forward and blocks it.
Back of a length, wide enough to be left alone.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Length ball, around off. Pushed towards point.
BEATEN! Right in the corridor of uncertainty and on a length. Young is glued to his crease while looking to block but the ball shapes away just enough and beats the bat.
A touch fuller, on the fourth stump. Young blocks it well.
Left alone as this quite wide outside off.
A touch fuller, on off. Young defends it well again.
Nice line and length. Good length, just outside off. Young gets forward and plays it with soft hands towards point.
Fuller ball, on off.  Blocked out by Latham.
Fuller ball, around off. Pushed to point.
Short of a length, outside off and left alone.
Well bowled this time! Fuller, around off. Latham is drawn towards the ball. He goes with his bat and pad close together and ends up getting an inside edge on the pads.
Well left. Length again, lands outside off and angles back in. Latham gets towards the ball, covers the stumps and then leaves it.
Length ball, wide outside off. Latham is not bothered with that line.
Good-length ball, wide enough for Young to leave it comfortably.
Just a single as this is pushed past cover.
FOUR! Nicely done! Length ball, outside off. Latham drives it past point and gets a boundary.
Review time! Latham has reviewed this LBW decision but this looks out. Well, scratch that. There is a big inside edge on it. Just like Gill on Day 1!

NOT OUT! Inside edge on that! Length ball, around off. Latham looks to block but the ball hits the pads right in front of the stump. Latham does review the LBW decision though. UltraEdge shows an inside edge and he is safe.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed back towards Sharma by Latham.
Good-length ball, on the fourth stump. Latham blocks it off the front foot.
Length ball, around off. Young is once again very solid in his defense.
Length ball, on off. Young stays in the crease and blocks it.
Full and on the pads. Flicked past deep mid-wicket for a couple.
Length ball, down the leg side. Young looks to flick but gets hit on the pads. Yadav enquires about the LBW but the ball was likely sliding down leg.
Short of a length, but similar line. Blocked out by Young again.
Yadav starts with a length ball, on off. Young taps it towards cover.
Who will bowl from the other end? Umesh Yadav it is!
Sharma serves a full and wide one. Latham will not chase that so early in the innings.
Length ball, just outside off. Latham works it towards mid-wicket.
Good length again, right on the off pole. Latham works it towards square leg.
Length ball, around off. Latham prods forward and taps it to point.
Length ball, on middle. Latham blocks it out. The hooter goes off in the stadium as the TV umpire has called this a no ball.
Nice angle back into the left-hander as Sharma is bowling 'round the wicket. It lands outside off and shapes away. Latham leaves this too.
Sharma starts with a length ball, way outside off. Latham leaves this one.
We are back! The New Zealand openers, Tom Latham and Will Young, walk out. India start with spin as Ravichandran Ashwin is given the ball. Here we go...

Now, the target is quite an in-between one! New Zealand have not been batted out of the game but if they do manage to chase this down. It will be a monumental effort, especially if we keep in mind the wicket which has shown signs of wear and tear now. The first target for them will be to get through the nervy period unscathed. India on the other hand, would love a couple of wickets at least.

Once again the Kiwi spinners disappointed. The pacers were excellent this morning, both actually got the Kiwis back into the game but the likes of Ajaz Patel, William Somerville, and Rachin Ravindra did not live upto the expectation. Just the one wicket between the three spinners and that is not what Williamson would have expected. Had they contributed too, New Zealand could have well been the favorites at the moment.

The declaration has finally come! INDIA HAVE SET A TARGET OF 284 FOR THE KIWIS! They have a little more than 100 overs to bowl their opposition out. India will be pretty pleased with the lead, especially after they were 5 down for just above 50. It was Iyer and Ashwin who put up a good stand and took India to safe shores. Saha and Iyer then continued the good work. Iyer perished shortly after getting to his half ton but Saha along with Patel then stitched another handy stand. The 4 added over 200 runs amongst them and have put India in control of this Test.
On a length, on off. Saha works it wide of deep mid-wicket for a couple.
On a length, on off. Saha pushes it to mid off.
Back of a length, around off. Patel pushes it to long on for one.
Length ball, on the pads. Worked to deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Nicely played! Length ball, around off. Saha punches it to deep cover. The man in the deep runs to his right and dives but, he fails to stop it.
Short of a length, outside off. Pulled down to long on for one.
Outside off, this is pushed through covers for one more.
Tosses it up on off, Saha looks to sweep, it goes off the inner half through square leg for one.
Outside off, this is guided to short third man.
Flatter and on off, it is pushed to covers.

The message was probably to up the ante! Right before this over started, the 12th man came out with drinks and presumably with a message for the batters. Patel steps down the track, does not get to the pitch of it but still swings, it goes off the inner half towards long on for one.
He plays more of a paddle scoop, this lands on off and turns back in. He gets it down to fine leg for one.
Half an appeal but turned down! This lands in the rough outside off and turns back in sharply. Patel gets his front leg out of the line of off and looks to defend. He misses to get hit on the pads.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Floats it up on off, Patel defends.
SIX! Over the fence! Finally some signs of aggression! Axar Patel steps down the track, he hits it with the turn and over the mid-wicket fence for a biggie.
Plays the paddle sweep now, down to fine leg for one.
Outside off, Patel hangs back and pushes it through covers for one.
Another one on the stumps, Saha keeps it out.
Floats it up on off, blocked.

Two! Fifty for Saha! This is a fine innings from Saha! He is not 100 percent fit, came out to bat when his side was in trouble and has really taken his side to safety now. A very hard-working knock. ... DAY 4, SESSION 3 ...

New Zealand would be disappointed with how the session panned out for them. After taking the wicket of Ashwin, they would have wanted to snip off the rest of the Indian batting early but Saha and Iyer stood in their way. The Kiwis started getting defensive with their bowling towards the end and it looked like they were playing for a draw at that point. The wicket of Iyer just before Tea though must have rekindled the belief in their camp. They would need to send the Indian lower order packing early post Tea though. Will that happen? Do join us at 2:30 pm Local (9 am GMT) for the last session!

What a session for India! They did lose Ashwin early and there would have been some nerves in the camp when that happened. But Saha joined Iyer and steadied the ship for the hosts. The two batters started scoring freely and have made sure that India have a solid lead on Day 4. Iyer did fall just before Tea but the advantage still pretty much lies with them.

A wicket just before Tea for New Zealand but the session has belonged to India! Their lead has crossed the 200-run mark and they are in a pretty comfortable position. The hosts would be happy with their show so far.

OUT! TAKEN! Shreyas Iyer has been strangled down the leg side. Yet again, it is Tim Southee who manages to provide the breakthrough. Much-needed wicket as the two were taking the game away. End of another top knock from Iyer. He will be disappointed with the way he got out but he will be pleased with the innings he has played. It is a short one, down the leg side, Iyer looks to pull, it does not bounce as much as he thought it would. It goes off the glove and the keeper, Tom Blundell, takes it inches above the ground. Iyer starts walking. The umpires want to check if it has carried and take it upstairs. Replays show it has. Iyer walks back and so do the other players as it is TEA ON DAY 4!
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Tim Southee

... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

A disappointing session for India. Cheteshwar Pujara did not hang in for a long time in the middle while the poor run for Ajinkya Rahane continued. Mayank Agarwal and Ravindra Jadeja were done in by some brilliant swing bowling by Tim Southee and departed in the same over. The stand between Shreyas Iyer and Ravichandran Ashwin has been quite aggressive and they have taken the lead to 133. India would know that chasing here is not going to be easy so anything around 200 could be a winning total here. Will they get to that magical 200-run mark? The next session will tell us. Join us at 12:10 pm Local (6:40 am GMT) to find out!

A brilliant show by the New Zealand bowlers. They took their time to find the right lines and lengths but once they did, there was no stopping them. Kyle Jamieson started things off by picking the early wicket and then Ajaz Patel too got in the act. Tim Southee said that he won't miss out on this and knocked two Indian batters in the same over. The pitch is deteriorating at a pace now and the Kiwis have to bat last here. If they take the next 5 wickets quickly post Lunch, they would be on track to win the Test.

What a session for New Zealand! They picked 4 big wickets and clawed back in the game. But they are by no means on top of the game as Iyer and Ashwin are looking quite good in the middle. The second session of the day will probably be the most important of the game.

Close! Iyer comes down the track but ends up yorking himself. He jams it out to covers.
Floats it up on middle, blocked.
Down the leg side, Iyer looks to flick but misses.
A double-wicket maiden for Southee! Fuller and on off, swinging away. It is driven to covers.
Length ball, down the leg side. Ashwin looks to flick but gets no bat on it.
Ravichandran Ashwin is the next batter. No signs of Wriddhiman Saha yet.
Review time! Ravindra Jadeja has taken the review against the LBW decision. No bat on it and three reds on Ball Tracker!

OUT! LBW! Three reds and Jadeja has to walk back! Not sure why he took the review there. That was plumb if there was no bat. Southee has two in the over and India have their backs against the walls now. They are effectively 100 for 5. Well, they could be 100 for 6 as we don't know if Wriddhiman Saha is going to bat. The swing proves to be the undoing of an Indian batter again. Southee goes full, gets it to tail back in nicely from outside off. Jadeja plants his front foot way too across, he then tries to flick but misses. It hits the back pad. Southee is celebrating as he appeals. The finger is raised. After a chat with Iyer, Jadeja reviews. To no avail though. He takes a review along with him.
Outside off, left alone.
Ravindra Jadeja walks out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Number 4 down and Southee gets his first! The morning session keeps getting better for the visitors. Southee has his 50th Test wicket against India. What a delivery! How skillful is this guy! The last delivery, landed on a similar length but then, it went on with the angle, Agarwal played a forward defensive stroke and it hit the middle. This time, it lands on a similar area, that is on a length and around off, moves away after pitching. Agarwal looks to do the same, he tries to play the original trajectory. The movement does him in though, it goes off the outside edge to the man at second slip. Latham makes no mistake.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Good length and on off, blocked.
A maiden then by Patel! On off, loopy delivery, played towards cover.
Angled into the pads, Iyer works it to mid-wicket.
Slightly shorter this time and on off, Iyer pushes it to covers.
Slower yet again, lands it on middle, gets it to dip. Iyer strokes it back to the bowler.
Slows it up and lands it on middle, Iyer lunges and defends.
Flatter and on middle, defended.

Drinks! A really good passage of play for New Zealand. They took time to find their mojo, but once they did, they have been right on the money. The lead for India has touched 100 but they would want to extend that by a lot.
Full ball, on off. Blocked out.

Beautiful bowling! Southee pushes the ball from wide of the crease. It comes in with that angle, lands outside off. Mayank Agarwal looks to block it from the crease but it shapes away and goes past the outside edge.
A single as this is pushed to mid off.
Beaten! Full ball, lands on off and shapes away. Iyer comes forward and looks to block but the ball goes past the bat.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
FOUR! THROUGH THE SLIPS! Length ball, around off. Iyer looks to block but gets the outside edge. The man at first slip is quite wide. The ball goes between him and the keeper to run to the fence.
Full ball, around off. Agarwal gets forward and blocks it.
Tossed up, wide outside off. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
Flatter ball, on off. Blocked out.
FOUR! Tossed up, on off. Mayank Agarwal comes down the track and takes it on the full. He hits it over mid off and slips and falls on the pitch. The ball runs to the fence.
Flatter ball, on off. It stays low but Mayank Agarwal gets his bat down in time and blocks it.
Darted on the pads. Iyer works it past square leg for one.
Short of a length, lands outside off and shapes away. Left alone.
Full and way outside off. Mayank Agarwal leaves it alone.
Kyle Jamieson bends his back and bowls a short one, on off. Mayank ducks under it.
Length ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal gets his head on top of the ball and blocks it.
Short of a length, outside off. Mayank Agarwal punches it to point but the fielder dives and stops it.
Short of a length, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on leg. Iyer blocks it out with ease.
The centurion of the first innings, Shreyas Iyer, walks out to bat.

OUT! LBW! PLUMB IN FRONT! Tossed up, lands on off and comes in with the angle. Rahane plays for the turn and looks to block. The ball hits his pad right in front of the stumps and the finger goes up. Rahane has a word with Agarwal but decides not to review it. That looked dead straight, to be honest. Rahane's poor run of form continues.
FOUR! Lovely stroke! Full ball, on off. Rahane nicely drives it to the cover fence.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Rahane looks to work it to the leg side but gets hit on the pads.
Loopy ball, on off. Rahane gets forward and taps it out.
Darted on the pads. Agarwal gets the inside edge towards deep square leg for one.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out by Rahane.
Short of a length, outside off. Punched to point but the fielder dives and stops the ball.
BEATEN! On a length, just outside off. Rahane has his feet glued to the crease and looks to poke at it. The ball shapes away a bit and goes past the outside edge.
Length ball, around off. Blocked out.
Short of a length, outside off. Rahane rides the bounce and taps it to the off side.
On a length, outside off. Rahane gets forward and then leaves it with ease.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed to cover.
Darted on the pads. Mayank Agarwal looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
Well bowled! Tossed up, on middle. Mayank Agarwal gets to the ball to block but gets the outside edge. It drops short of first slip though.
Fuller this time, on middle. Mayank Agarwal goes back and deals with the low bounce to block it.
FOUR! Punished! Short ball, down the leg side. Mayank Agarwal pulls it nicely to the square leg fence.
Flatter ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal goes back and blocks it.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Low full toss, on off. Pushed to mid off.
Short of a length, outside off. Rahane looks to cut it away but the ball bounces a bit more than usual and goes past the outside edge.

Well bowled! Full ball, lands on off and comes back in. Rahane is stuck in the crease while looking to block. The ball goes onto hit the pads and there is an appeal for LBW but it is turned down. Good decision as Ball Tracker shows that the ball is going over the stumps.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Ajinkya Rahane walks out to bat.
Review time! Kane Williamson reviews this for caught behind. Spike on UltraEdge!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Kyle Jamieson strikes early! Short ball, down the leg side. Cheteshwar Pujara looks to leave it alone. Tom Blundell gathers it and is up in arms and so is Kyle Jamieson. But the umpire is unmoved. The keeper and bowler convince Kane Williamson to take the review. There is a spike on UltraEdge as the ball passes the gloves! Pujara has to walk back now.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Flatter ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal goes back and blocks it.
Full ball, on off. Pushed to cover.
Loopy ball, on off. Mayank Agarwal gets to the pitch of the ball and blocks it.
Darted down the leg side. Left alone.
Stays very low! Shorter ball, outside off. Mayank Agarwal goes for the pull but stays very, very low. The keeper does well to gather it.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Pujara works it past mid-wicket for one.
Ajaz Patel is on now.
Back of a length this time, outside off. Agarwal pushes it to covers from the crease.
Length ball, just outside off. Pushed to cover.
Fuller and closer to the off pole. Mayank Agarwal blocks it.
Short of a length, lands outside off and comes back in. But it is left alone by Mayank Agarwal.
Length ball, on the sixth stump. Mayank Agarwal puts in a nice stride and pushes it to point.
Full and on the pads. Pujara works it to the right of square leg for one.
Fuller and wider outside off. Agarwal leaves it with ease.
Short of a length, just outside off. Mayank Agarwal covers the stumps and then leaves it.
On a length, around off. Blocked out.
Full and on the pads again. Clipped away nicely but the man at square leg dives to his right and stops it.
Full and on the pads. Pujara works it past square leg for one.
Fuller ball, on off. Blocked out.

Better line and length! Probably the first time that Kyle Jamieson has bowled the perfect delivery this morning. Short of a length, just outside off. Pujara looks to block from the crease but there is a bit of extra bounce and it takes the outside edge. The man at first slip dives to his right but it drops short of him.
Full and on the pads. Clipped away and the man at square leg dives over it. Two taken.
Short of a length, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara cuts it well but the man at point stops it.
Short of a length, around off. Worked to mid-wicket.
Length ball, around off. Cheteshwar Pujara comes forward and blocks it.
Kyle Jamieson fires a full one, on the pads. Mayank Agarwal looks to flick but gets hit on the pads. The ball rolls away and a leg bye is taken.
Short of a length, on off. Pujara pushes it back to the bowler.
Full again, on middle and off. Pushed towards mid on.
Full ball, on off. Pujara blocks it with ease.
Full ball, on off. Pujara gets forward and blocks it.
Full and on the pads. Pujara clips it well. The man at square leg dives but over the ball. It is cut off by deep backward square leg. Two runs.
Full and down the leg side. Pujara misses the flick.
Tim Southee will start from the other end.
Short of a length, around off. Blocked out. 9 from the first over.
FOUR! Through the slips! On a length, drawing Mayank Agarwal forward to block. The ball takes the outside edge but runs between first slip and gully and runs to the fence.
On a length, around off. Mayank taps it towards cover.
Again. Length ball, on the pads. Clipped to deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Easy pickings! First runs of the day! Length ball, down the leg side. Pujara clips it nicely to the fine leg fence.
Kyle starts with a full one, down the leg side. Pujara goes for the flick but misses.

We are set for the day to get underway! New Zealand have made their way out to the middle. Cheteshwar Pujara and Mayank Agarwal take the crease. Kyle Jamieson is set to start with the ball. Here we go...

Ravichandran Ashwin is down for a chat. He says that they stuck together well as a unit. Adds that they knew it would be hard work but they stuck well as a group and everyone did the job well. Informs that there is a bit more in the pitch when bowling from the River End and it will get tougher to bat on.

PITCH REPORT - Deep Dasgupta is down for the pitch report. He says that the pitch got more and more responsive to the bowlers on Day 3. Ajit Agarkar joins him and says that the cracks have opened up quite a bit and should pose problems for the batters. Deep Dasgupta says that there hasn't been a whole lot of wear and tear as the weather has been quite cool.

The pitch is opening up now and it will get more and more difficult to bat on in the coming two days. We saw quite a few deliveries staying low and turning sharply on Day 3 and the Indian spinners would be licking their fingers as they will bowl last on this surface. It is therefore imperative from New Zealand's perspective to keep India to a very low score here. If the Kiwis end up getting a target of around 300, it might get tough for them. Therefore, how they bowl here in the first session will be very important to see. Stay with us for more updates.

Hello and a very warm welcome to the action of Day 4 of this first Test. The first hour of play here will be very crucial. If the Kiwis manage to take a couple of early wickets, then we could see them clawing back in the game. If India do not lose early wickets and put on a good stand, then it is quite likely that the Kiwis will have a tough target to chase down in the fourth innings. With everything to play for, expect both the teams to go hard at each other. With that, welcome once again to our coverage.
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then. We had an exciting Day 3 and Day 4 promises to be better. The match is by no means over and New Zealand can still get back on top. But for that, they need to pick early wickets on Day 4. The first hour will be very critical in the context of the game. Do join us on 28th November at 9:30 am local (4 am GMT) for the action of Day 4. Cheers!

Axar Patel is down for a chat. He says that it is not easy, when they were batting well it did not seem easy, they needed to be patient and they were rewarded. Informs he was using the crease well and the round-arm action balls were working well and it was causing problems. Reckons the wicket is getting slower and the odd ball is turning and staying low but if you apply yourself, runs are on offer.

A brilliant day of Test cricket for India. They started picking up wickets early and then took wickets at regular intervals. With the pitch opening up, it was expected that the spinners will play a big role and the Indian spinners shared 9 wickets between them. The star was Axar Patel with his 5-wicket haul and the Indian bowling attack sent back the middle and lower order of New Zealand back in no time. Kiwis would be quite disappointed with the way they batted but Kyle Jamieson getting the late wicket of Shubman Gill would have been a relief for them.

The umpires have offered the light to the batters and that will be Stumps on Day 3! New Zealand had the perfect little session of play here but it was India, who will be the happier side going back. They lead by 63 runs and have the advantage here in this Test.
Pujara skips down the track, makes it into a low full toss and whips it wide of mid on for one.
Pujara comes down the track, Patel bowls it short. Defended.
On middle, blocked.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through square leg, they run the first one quickly but settle for it.

Very close! Flight, it starts outside off and then drifts back in. Agarwal initially looks to drive but the realizes he is not going to get to the pitch of the ball. He looks to defend, this goes off the inside edge past the off pole and down to the fine leg region for two.
Fuller and on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Change. With the light fading, Kane Williamson brings on Ajaz Patel.
EDGY FOUR! Soft hands! On off, shapes away. Pujara leans forward and tries to defend, this goes off the outside edge through point for a boundary.
Fuller and on middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Length and on off again, it is kept out nicely.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.

Almost another one! That inswinger is causing problems! Length and outside off, this lands and jags back in. Pujara looks to defend but leaves a gap between bat and pad. It sneaks through and just goes past the off pole.
Outside off, left alone.
Out comes the light meter. The umpires are taking measurements currently. We are set to continue, for now.
On middle, Agarwal works it to mid on.
Another one outside off, Agarwal shoulders arms to this one.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length and on off, Agarwal blocks it out.
Just outside off, left alone.
Good length and on off, Agarwal defends it.

FOUR! Can be called a fortunate boundary! Pujara, right at the end, decided to play that shot. Short and on middle, he intially looks to duck under it but then realises that it is not bouncing a lot. He then opens the face of the bat at the very end, goes between gully and the slip fielder for a boundary.
On off, blocked.
On middle, defended.

This one stays low! That spot, there is a spot outside off where if the ball lands, tends to stay low. Kyle Jamieson probably landed it there. It does not get up. Pujara is beaten as he tries to block.
The outswinger to welcome Pujara! Slightly fuller and on off, shaping away. Defended.
Cheteshwar Pujara walks out to bat.

OUT! TIMBER! 50th Test wicket for Kyle Jamieson! He just continues to impress. Strikes on the very first ball, just the start his side wanted. The half centurion of the first innings falls for just a single run. Kyle Jamieson is also the fastest to 50 wickets in Tests for the Kiwis. Right on the money from the word go. Length and on off, jags back in a touch. Gill probably should be coming forward on a wicket that is not bouncing a lot. His feet though are glued to the crease. He looks to defend it half-heartedly. It sneaks past the bat, clips the pad and hits the stumps. Kyle Jamieson is delighted. There is still time for another wicket.
Outside off, Agarwal guides it to point.
BEATEN! That is a beauty! Length and on off, angles in at first but lands and leaves the batter. Agarwal is squared up as he tries to block. Gets beaten.
Another one on a length and around off, blocked.
Gill is off the mark too! Fuller and on off, this is driven through covers for one.
Another one on a length and around off, Gill guides it to point.
India and Agarwal are underway! The lead also touches 50. Around off, shapes away. Agarwal looks to defend, this goes off the outer half through point for one.

So, that is it from the first Test! It went down to the wire. In the end, there was no result possible and that was probably the right result. The action now moves to Mumbai for the second and the final Test. That game begins on the 3rd of December, it starts at 9:30 am local (4 am GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Shreyas Iyer is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH! He says that if they had won the game, it would have been icing on the cake. Adds that his mindset was to face as many deliveries as possible and the situation demanded that he curb his attacking instincts. Credits Ashwin and Saha for the way they batted and that he is proud of getting out of a difficult situation to put a big total for New Zealand to chase. Mentions that New Zealand got off to a great start on Day 5 but once they got a sniff, the bowlers decided to attack.

The Indian skipper, Ajinkya Rahane, says they tried their best, it was a good game, New Zealand played well. Adds he is proud of how they came back in the second innings, especially the pacers, they bowled really well. Mentions they were looking to bowl 5 to 6 overs on Day 4, they needed that partnership between Saha and Axar as they lost a lot of wickets at the start. Adds the conversation with the umpires was about the lights and he feels the call made by the umpires was right. States he felt the spinners had a key role to play on this wicket and it was all about rotating the bowlers and they bowled really well. Credits Iyer for the way he played and he is really happy for him.

Kane Williamson, the skipper of New Zealand, says that with the light it has been touch and go throughout the game. Adds that his team hung in there and did not give up. Says that all three results were possible on the final day and India have a great bowling attack but his team hung in there. Adds that players like William Somerville and Rachin Ravindra had a great experience in this game. Mentions that the two pacers who played were outstanding and the batters too adjusted really well against the Indian attack. Says that it was a great experience and the batters would look to make more adjustments moving forward in the series.
Stay tuned for the presentation.

Ravichandran Ashwin says they were keeping things under control and were bowling in good areas, they knew if they got time, they would cause problems but the light was going to be an issue and they knew it. States Test cricket is really hard, you need to want it, there is a lot of hard work and he enjoys the format. States the runs, the wickets won't really matter, it is the memories that will and he wants to take some good memories. Adds the wicket was good and it played well, Ravindra played really well and so did Ajaz Patel and he hopes people enjoyed the game.

Entering Day 5, an Indian win looked most likely. The Kiwis too knew it was going to be an uphill task to chase this down. Their approach was to save the Test throughout the day and they managed to do by just. A hard-fought draw and probably the right result to a game that was a spectacle.

India had a decent lead of 49 runs but their second innings did not start as per plan and they found themselves at 51 for 5. But it was Shreyas Iyer once again who saved the team. He scored a fifty and bailed them out. Ravichandran Ashwin, Axar Patel and Wriddhiman Saha, who also scored a fifty made sure that New Zealand had a pretty huge total to chase down in just over a day.

New Zealand started their reply brilliantly though. Will Young and Tom Latham were superb with their opening stand and both scored their fifties. They were unfortunate to miss out on their tons, but it was due to their efforts that New Zealand got close to India's total as the middle order did not contribute much. It was no surprise that the Indian spinners ruled the roost as they shared 9 wickets between them with Axar Patel getting a 5-wicket haul.

Earlier in the game, it was Shreyas Iyer who was the hero for India in the first innings. The rest of the batters did get starts but it was Iyer who bailed them out from a tough situation and got them to a respectable score. As far as the bowling is concerned, Tim Southee was the start as he took a 5-wicket haul and demolished the Indian middle order early on Day 2.

But the Indian spinners ruled the roost post Tea. Axar Patel started things off by taking the wicket of Henry Nicholls and that triggered a collapse. Ravindra Jadeja was the main bowler in the last session though as his 3 wickets in that session put India just 1 wicket away from a memorable victory. But nature had different plans and bad light denied them a victory.

The Kiwis did lose Will Young in their chase but William Somerville and Tom Latham were very impressive with the way they batted. New Zealand did not lose a single wicket in the first session of Day 5 and there would have been plenty of nerves in the Indian camp. But after Lunch, things turned around. Somerville fell and Latham too had to walk back to the hut. They received another big blow in the form of Ross Taylor just before Tea and Kane Williamson was the lone man standing.

Phew, what a finish! What a finish! New Zealand have saved the Test by the barest of margins here. It looked like India would seal this one but the light hasn't worked in their favour. Rachin Ravindra and Ajaz Patel would have had their hearts in the mouth in the last half hour of play but they have managed to save this Test!

Stopped for bad light! Not called off yet. Not called off. But we have stopped for bad light. If the light improves, we can resume again. There are handshakes in the New Zealand camp already but there are another 11 minutes of play possible though! Well, well, I think they are calling it off! YUP, PLAY CALLED OFF! Kane Williamson walks out with his side and there are handshakes all around! What a nail-biting finish! THE FIRST TEST ENDS IN A DRAW!
Patel has negotitaed the six balls well! This lands on off and turns back in. Defended.

Changes to over the wicket and fires it on off, Patel does manage to keep it out.

Flatter and on off, Patel blocks.

Loopy ball on middle, Patel defends it nicely.
Another chat between the umpires. The on-air commentators are saying that it has gotten a bit brighter now! The sun has now come out of the clouds and that has helped India in this situation.
Floats it up on off, Rachin Ravindra prods forward and plays it to mid on.

Patel keeps it out easily! On off, Patel is solid in defense.
A single! Patel has one ball to negotiate! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.

On off, blocked.

On middle, defended.

Another one way too full, easily played onto the ground.

Two! On the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for two.
Flatter and on middle, it is kept out.
On off, defended.
On off, Patel pushes it to covers.
On off, blocked.

Down the leg side, left alone.
Quicker and on middle, kept out.

Angled into the pads, this is worked to mid-wicket.

FOUR BYES! This one keeps really low! This lands on off and then turns away. It beats the outside edge of the bat as Rachin Ravindra tries to defend. Stays very low and goes between the legs of the keeper for a boundary in the third man region.
